He said you all are
printing our money

00:09:29.980 --> 00:09:31.410 align:middle line:90%
and charging us interest for it.

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:32.880 align:middle line:90%
He said that's not right.

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:35.210 align:middle line:84%
And so he was trying to
nationalize the Federal

00:09:35.210 --> 00:09:39.390 align:middle line:84%
Reserve, which, you know, is
actually composed of 12 Federal

00:09:39.390 --> 00:09:42.470 align:middle line:84%
Reserve branches, all
of which are 100% owned

00:09:42.470 --> 00:09:44.380 align:middle line:90%
by the banks in their district.

00:09:44.380 --> 00:09:47.780 align:middle line:84%
So to avoid that, they agreed
to rebate their profits

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:49.390 align:middle line:90%
to the government.

00:09:49.390 --> 00:09:54.830 align:middle line:84%
So now, the bonds that the
Feds had bought, the securities

00:09:54.830 --> 00:09:59.430 align:middle line:84%
that the Fed holds, it returns
the interest to the government.

00:09:59.430 --> 00:10:02.050 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So the bottom
line for the consumer,

00:10:02.050 --> 00:10:05.914 align:middle line:84%
for the bottom 80%
of us is-- and I

00:10:05.914 --> 00:10:07.830 align:middle line:84%
want to go into the
history a little bit, too,

00:10:07.830 --> 00:10:09.680 align:middle line:84%
of how we ended up
in this situation.

00:10:09.680 --> 00:10:12.016 align:middle line:84%
Because it sounds to me, what
you're talking about, just

00:10:12.016 --> 00:10:13.640 align:middle line:84%
talking about your
friend, who's having

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:16.570 align:middle line:84%
to put whatever
aspect of his business

00:10:16.570 --> 00:10:19.640 align:middle line:84%
he's having to put on
his credit card at 16%,

00:10:19.640 --> 00:10:21.910 align:middle line:84%
now that's going to be
passed along to the consumer

00:10:21.910 --> 00:10:22.920 align:middle line:90%
ultimately.

00:10:22.920 --> 00:10:26.480 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we look at the inflation
happening and a lot of people

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:29.930 align:middle line:84%
put articles out, some of them
conspiracies, some of them

00:10:29.930 --> 00:10:32.560 align:middle line:84%
are actually quite right
on as to why that might be.

00:10:32.560 --> 00:10:35.480 align:middle line:84%
But there are many factors
that are coming into play

00:10:35.480 --> 00:10:38.180 align:middle line:84%
as to the increase
in price of goods.

00:10:38.180 --> 00:10:39.910 align:middle line:90%
So let's go back--

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:40.630 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Can I-- I just
wanted to-- quick--

00:10:40.630 --> 00:10:41.546 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes, please.

00:10:41.546 --> 00:10:44.310 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: So that was $454
billion on the federal debt.

00:10:44.310 --> 00:10:49.180 align:middle line:10%
Then there's $750 billion that
the banks collect in interest.

00:10:49.180 --> 00:10:51.020 align:middle line:10%
So let's assume
hypothetically-- it

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:53.110 align:middle line:10%
wouldn't be easy to
nationalize the whole system.

00:10:53.110 --> 00:10:56.310 align:middle line:10%
But let's assume
hypothetically that banking

00:10:56.310 --> 00:10:58.440 align:middle line:10%
were a public
utility like water,

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:00.450 align:middle line:10%
like highways, et cetera.

00:11:00.450 --> 00:11:03.050 align:middle line:84%
So the profits would
go back to the people.

00:11:03.050 --> 00:11:06.090 align:middle line:84%
That way, if you add
the 750 and the 454,

00:11:06.090 --> 00:11:09.290 align:middle line:84%
you get more than the
$1.1 trillion that

00:11:09.290 --> 00:11:10.540 align:middle line:90%
we're paying in income taxes.

00:11:10.540 --> 00:11:12.680 align:middle line:84%
So you could either
eliminate income taxes,

00:11:12.680 --> 00:11:14.230 align:middle line:84%
or you could have
an extra trillion

00:11:14.230 --> 00:11:16.679 align:middle line:84%
to play with, to do
all sorts of services

00:11:16.679 --> 00:11:17.720 align:middle line:90%
that we desperately need.

00:11:17.720 --> 00:11:18.390 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It makes total sense.

00:11:18.390 --> 00:11:20.765 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you've been talking
about this for quite a while.

00:11:20.765 --> 00:11:22.820 align:middle line:84%
And there are other
examples where this already

00:11:22.820 --> 00:11:25.680 align:middle line:84%
exists that we're going to get
into, even one in the United

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:28.540 align:middle line:84%
States in the case of one
state, which you use as a really

00:11:28.540 --> 00:11:30.390 align:middle line:84%
wonderful example
of what could happen

00:11:30.390 --> 00:11:32.289 align:middle line:90%
if we went that way as a nation.

00:11:32.289 --> 00:11:34.830 align:middle line:84%
Do you mind going back and doing
over a little bit of history

00:11:34.830 --> 00:11:36.950 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:11:36.950 --> 00:11:39.820 align:middle line:84%
Let's start way back,
more toward the beginning

00:11:39.820 --> 00:11:42.590 align:middle line:90%
of the United States.

00:11:42.590 --> 00:11:47.150 align:middle line:84%
Would you want to go pre War
of 1812, post War of 1812?

00:11:47.150 --> 00:11:48.290 align:middle line:90%
Where do you want to begin?

00:11:48.290 --> 00:11:51.097 align:middle line:84%
But we have to put Alexander
Hamilton in the mix somewhere.

00:11:51.097 --> 00:11:51.680 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:11:51.680 --> 00:11:54.830 align:middle line:90%
Well, I would go back to 1691.

00:11:54.830 --> 00:11:57.710 align:middle line:84%
That was when the
colonists came up

00:11:57.710 --> 00:12:00.480 align:middle line:84%
with this rather brilliant
system of just funding

00:12:00.480 --> 00:12:02.180 align:middle line:84%
their government
by printing money.

00:12:02.180 --> 00:12:04.450 align:middle line:84%
I mean, today printing
money has a bad name

00:12:04.450 --> 00:12:07.120 align:middle line:84%
because everybody thinks,
oh, hyperinflation.

00:12:07.120 --> 00:12:08.820 align:middle line:84%
And we're going
into hyperinflation.

00:12:08.820 --> 00:12:11.890 align:middle line:84%
But the way they did
it then, the choices

00:12:11.890 --> 00:12:15.810 align:middle line:84%
were to borrow from the British
bankers, who were not actually

00:12:15.810 --> 00:12:17.620 align:middle line:90%
lending gold.

00:12:17.620 --> 00:12:19.260 align:middle line:84%
They were lending
paper money that

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:20.760 align:middle line:90%
was supposedly backed by gold.

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:23.270 align:middle line:84%
So you were still just
borrowing some money

00:12:23.270 --> 00:12:25.050 align:middle line:84%
that was just
created by somebody.

00:12:25.050 --> 00:12:27.650 align:middle line:84%
But it was created by
the banks privately.

00:12:27.650 --> 00:12:30.910 align:middle line:84%
So the alternative
was for the government

00:12:30.910 --> 00:12:34.540 align:middle line:84%
to issue these paper
credits and pay

00:12:34.540 --> 00:12:37.930 align:middle line:84%
for goods and services,
workers, and materials.

00:12:37.930 --> 00:12:40.820 align:middle line:84%
And then because these
were things, like,

00:12:40.820 --> 00:12:43.550 align:middle line:84%
it started out it
was a little war

00:12:43.550 --> 00:12:46.640 align:middle line:84%
that the governor of
Massachusetts had to fund.

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:48.810 align:middle line:84%
And he couldn't find
anyone to borrow from.

00:12:48.810 --> 00:12:50.980 align:middle line:84%
So he just issued these
little paper receipts

00:12:50.980 --> 00:12:53.196 align:middle line:84%
to the soldiers
that basically said,

00:12:53.196 --> 00:12:56.240 align:middle line:84%
you know, you have delivered
x amount of service

00:12:56.240 --> 00:12:58.210 align:middle line:84%
to the community, and
the community owes you,

00:12:58.210 --> 00:13:01.070 align:middle line:84%
and you can spend those little
receipts in the community.

00:13:01.070 --> 00:13:02.870 align:middle line:84%
And then they
circulated as money.

00:13:02.870 --> 00:13:07.165 align:middle line:84%
And they retained their value
because they were accepted back

00:13:07.165 --> 00:13:08.510 align:middle line:90%
as taxes.

00:13:08.510 --> 00:13:11.600 align:middle line:84%
California tried to do that
recently, issue warrants.

00:13:11.600 --> 00:13:13.630 align:middle line:84%
But they wouldn't take
them back in taxes.

00:13:13.630 --> 00:13:15.767 align:middle line:84%
So it's like, you
can take our IOUs,

00:13:15.767 --> 00:13:17.350 align:middle line:84%
but we're not going
to take them back.

00:13:17.350 --> 00:13:18.516 align:middle line:90%
So of course it didn't work.

00:13:18.516 --> 00:13:20.931 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Did that with Bosnia
on the currency recently.

00:13:20.931 --> 00:13:23.430 align:middle line:84%
I could buy it, but I couldn't
sell it back to the Bosnians.

00:13:23.430 --> 00:13:24.190 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:13:24.190 --> 00:13:24.950 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:13:24.950 --> 00:13:25.490 align:middle line:90%
Well, OK.

00:13:25.490 --> 00:13:27.970 align:middle line:84%
And right here, I brought
these because they're so fun.

00:13:27.970 --> 00:13:30.840 align:middle line:84%
We have these little-- they're
antiqued reproductions.

00:13:30.840 --> 00:13:32.430 align:middle line:90%
Here's one.

00:13:32.430 --> 00:13:34.532 align:middle line:84%
One of them is from the
state of Massachusetts.

00:13:34.532 --> 00:13:35.990 align:middle line:84%
Here it is, state
of Massachusetts,

00:13:35.990 --> 00:13:37.750 align:middle line:90%
as a matter of fact, for $8.

00:13:37.750 --> 00:13:38.990 align:middle line:90%
So what are these?

00:13:38.990 --> 00:13:40.900 align:middle line:84%
Another one here
is in shillings.

00:13:40.900 --> 00:13:42.659 align:middle line:84%
These are little
certificates that--

00:13:42.659 --> 00:13:43.450 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: All right.

00:13:43.450 --> 00:13:45.080 align:middle line:90%
Well these were actually later.

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:47.690 align:middle line:90%
So this one's issued 1780.

00:13:47.690 --> 00:13:50.540 align:middle line:84%
So that's like 100
years later, and that

00:13:50.540 --> 00:13:53.700 align:middle line:84%
would be during the
Revolutionary War.

00:13:53.700 --> 00:13:55.540 align:middle line:84%
And now one problem
with these was

00:13:55.540 --> 00:13:59.000 align:middle line:84%
that they were issued-- these
particular ones-- is that they

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.300 align:middle line:90%
were issued as promissory notes.

00:14:01.300 --> 00:14:04.750 align:middle line:84%
In other words, they say that
the government will pay you

00:14:04.750 --> 00:14:09.890 align:middle line:84%
in gold basically when the
Revolutionary War is over.

00:14:09.890 --> 00:14:13.140 align:middle line:84%
So they weren't actually
legal tender in themselves.

00:14:13.140 --> 00:14:15.030 align:middle line:84%
And so at the end
of the war, that's

00:14:15.030 --> 00:14:19.090 align:middle line:84%
where we get into the
Alexander Hamilton problem.

00:14:19.090 --> 00:14:20.660 align:middle line:84%
They owed all this
money that they

00:14:20.660 --> 00:14:25.650 align:middle line:84%
wouldn't have had to owe if
they had paid in legal tender,

00:14:25.650 --> 00:14:27.860 align:middle line:90%
in straight fiat money.

00:14:27.860 --> 00:14:31.050 align:middle line:84%
And plus, of course, they
owed the French in gold.

00:14:31.050 --> 00:14:33.750 align:middle line:84%
And the French weren't going
to take these pieces of paper.

00:14:33.750 --> 00:14:36.230 align:middle line:84%
So that's why
Hamilton had to set up

00:14:36.230 --> 00:14:41.510 align:middle line:84%
this bank on the British
model, where they took all

00:14:41.510 --> 00:14:43.510 align:middle line:84%
the gold that the
government did have.

00:14:43.510 --> 00:14:47.540 align:middle line:84%
And then they issued 10 times
that many notes, banknotes.

00:14:47.540 --> 00:14:49.680 align:middle line:84%
And everybody took
them because they

00:14:49.680 --> 00:14:53.002 align:middle line:84%
thought they were
redeemable in gold.

00:14:53.002 --> 00:14:53.960 align:middle line:90%
So it worked very well.

00:14:53.960 --> 00:14:56.210 align:middle line:84%
And they actually got the
economy back on its feet.

00:14:56.210 --> 00:15:00.330 align:middle line:84%
But what it did was
it put us all in debt

00:15:00.330 --> 00:15:01.972 align:middle line:90%
for the last 200 years.

00:15:01.972 --> 00:15:03.680 align:middle line:84%
We've been in debt to
this banking system

00:15:03.680 --> 00:15:04.580 align:middle line:84%
that we didn't have
to be in debt to.

00:15:04.580 --> 00:15:05.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So we're still into
that fractionalized banking

00:15:05.460 --> 00:15:06.000 align:middle line:90%
system.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:07.320 align:middle line:90%
And then what happened?

00:15:07.320 --> 00:15:09.040 align:middle line:84%
Because I showed
you this off camera.

00:15:09.040 --> 00:15:15.120 align:middle line:84%
So now we have some notes here,
$5 notes, from the War of 1812.

00:15:15.120 --> 00:15:19.100 align:middle line:84%
So in taking a look at these,
you said there was a problem.

00:15:19.100 --> 00:15:21.714 align:middle line:84%
This is where something
else historical

00:15:21.714 --> 00:15:22.880 align:middle line:90%
occurred around these notes.

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:24.100 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:15:24.100 --> 00:15:27.340 align:middle line:84%
Hamilton set up
the first US bank.

00:15:27.340 --> 00:15:31.120 align:middle line:84%
And originally it was 80%
percent publicly owned.

00:15:31.120 --> 00:15:35.100 align:middle line:84%
But in the end, the whole
thing wound up being privatized

00:15:35.100 --> 00:15:38.169 align:middle line:84%
and largely to the
British bankers,

00:15:38.169 --> 00:15:39.460 align:middle line:90%
which is what they didn't want.

00:15:39.460 --> 00:15:40.350 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But his
intention was that it

00:15:40.350 --> 00:15:41.482 align:middle line:90%
would be publicly owned?

00:15:41.482 --> 00:15:42.440 align:middle line:90%
Was that the intention?

00:15:42.440 --> 00:15:43.023 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:15:43.023 --> 00:15:44.910 align:middle line:84%
He actually was opposed
to privatizing it.

00:15:44.910 --> 00:15:46.500 align:middle line:84%
But because they
needed the money,

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:48.770 align:middle line:84%
they wound up
selling the shares.

00:15:48.770 --> 00:15:52.790 align:middle line:84%
And Jefferson was opposed
to this bank all along.

00:15:52.790 --> 00:15:59.020 align:middle line:84%
And so he was instrumental
in getting the charter

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:01.410 align:middle line:84%
not being renewed
when it expired.

00:16:01.410 --> 00:16:03.790 align:middle line:84%
But then the War
of 1812 came along,

00:16:03.790 --> 00:16:06.496 align:middle line:84%
and nobody really knows
what it was about.

00:16:06.496 --> 00:16:07.120 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:16:07.120 --> 00:16:08.650 align:middle line:90%
What was it about?

00:16:08.650 --> 00:16:10.850 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Well,
allegedly, rumor has it,

00:16:10.850 --> 00:16:16.190 align:middle line:84%
it was created by the
bankers to put us in debt.

00:16:16.190 --> 00:16:18.720 align:middle line:84%
The British bankers
wanted their colony back.

00:16:18.720 --> 00:16:21.490 align:middle line:84%
And so that's what
war is always about,

00:16:21.490 --> 00:16:24.390 align:middle line:84%
or that is a factor
always in war,

00:16:24.390 --> 00:16:27.570 align:middle line:84%
is that the bankers, the
international bankers,

00:16:27.570 --> 00:16:29.810 align:middle line:84%
the big bankers,
fund both sides.

00:16:29.810 --> 00:16:31.320 align:middle line:90%
And everybody gets in debt.

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:34.434 align:middle line:84%
And then that's how they capture
you in this debt machine.

00:16:34.434 --> 00:16:37.100 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And that's right up to
modern day as a matter of fact.

00:16:37.100 --> 00:16:39.110 align:middle line:90%
That practice hasn't changed.

00:16:39.110 --> 00:16:44.460 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: So then Madison
had to set up the second US

00:16:44.460 --> 00:16:47.330 align:middle line:84%
bank in order to do the
same thing over again,

00:16:47.330 --> 00:16:50.200 align:middle line:84%
where they would do
fractional reserve lending.

00:16:50.200 --> 00:16:54.400 align:middle line:84%
And then Andrew Jackson-- I
mean that bank was seriously

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:55.000 align:middle line:90%
corrupt.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:58.190 align:middle line:84%
And Andrew Jackson
shut that one down.

00:16:58.190 --> 00:17:02.010 align:middle line:84%
And then we had a whole
period of free banking.

00:17:02.010 --> 00:17:03.270 align:middle line:90%
But it didn't work out well.

00:17:03.270 --> 00:17:06.760 align:middle line:84%
There were all
these wildcat banks

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:10.710 align:middle line:84%
that would actually issue
10 times as many banknotes

00:17:10.710 --> 00:17:11.450 align:middle line:90%
as you had gold.

00:17:11.450 --> 00:17:13.740 align:middle line:90%
I was fairly reasonable.

00:17:13.740 --> 00:17:16.214 align:middle line:84%
But the wildcat banks
would do worse than that.

00:17:16.214 --> 00:17:17.880 align:middle line:84%
They would just issue
an issue, and they

00:17:17.880 --> 00:17:19.256 align:middle line:90%
had nothing backing it.

00:17:19.256 --> 00:17:20.630 align:middle line:84%
And when people
figured that out,

00:17:20.630 --> 00:17:24.579 align:middle line:84%
they would all rush to cash
in their banknotes at once.

00:17:24.579 --> 00:17:26.930 align:middle line:84%
And there would be
a run on the banks.

00:17:26.930 --> 00:17:29.730 align:middle line:84%
And there would be
a banking crisis.

00:17:29.730 --> 00:17:32.480 align:middle line:84%
And that happened, on
average, every six years

00:17:32.480 --> 00:17:35.090 align:middle line:84%
for the entire 19th
century leading up

00:17:35.090 --> 00:17:38.795 align:middle line:84%
to the-- that was the excuse
for the Federal Reserve.

00:17:38.795 --> 00:17:40.920 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: The establishment
of the Federal Reserve.

00:17:40.920 --> 00:17:41.960 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:17:41.960 --> 00:17:44.540 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: In there there
was the-- in the Civil War,

00:17:44.540 --> 00:17:48.680 align:middle line:84%
Lincoln went back to what
the colonists had done, which

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:53.730 align:middle line:84%
was just issue paper
outright, issue money to pay

00:17:53.730 --> 00:17:56.550 align:middle line:90%
for part of the war.

00:17:56.550 --> 00:17:58.460 align:middle line:84%
He didn't fund the
entire war that way.

00:17:58.460 --> 00:18:00.700 align:middle line:84%
But it worked very
well, the greenbacks.

00:18:00.700 --> 00:18:04.350 align:middle line:84%
And the North managed
to win the war.

00:18:04.350 --> 00:18:08.540 align:middle line:84%
And also with that extra money
added to the money supply,

00:18:08.540 --> 00:18:10.840 align:middle line:90%
they funded the railroads.

00:18:10.840 --> 00:18:13.700 align:middle line:84%
I mean that was his big
contribution to commerce

00:18:13.700 --> 00:18:16.360 align:middle line:84%
was getting this railroad all
the way across the country.

00:18:16.360 --> 00:18:18.090 align:middle line:84%
And there were many
other developments.

00:18:18.090 --> 00:18:20.080 align:middle line:84%
I mean, business was
booming during that time

00:18:20.080 --> 00:18:23.300 align:middle line:84%
because there was extra money
around to conduct it with.

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:25.650 align:middle line:84%
But of course then he
passed away, or, sorry,

00:18:25.650 --> 00:18:26.796 align:middle line:90%
was assassinated.

00:18:26.796 --> 00:18:27.920 align:middle line:90%
Yes, passed away violently.

00:18:27.920 --> 00:18:28.980 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: In an untimely manner.

00:18:28.980 --> 00:18:29.563 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:18:29.563 --> 00:18:31.380 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:36.320 align:middle line:84%
But following the greenbacks,
which I think was 1862,

00:18:36.320 --> 00:18:39.460 align:middle line:84%
there was the National
Banking Act of 1863

00:18:39.460 --> 00:18:42.580 align:middle line:90%
and then another one in 1865.

00:18:42.580 --> 00:18:46.280 align:middle line:84%
And in that system,
the idea was to try

00:18:46.280 --> 00:18:48.682 align:middle line:84%
to get the banks
on a stable system

00:18:48.682 --> 00:18:51.140 align:middle line:84%
because nobody could tell what
these bank notes were worth.

00:18:51.140 --> 00:18:53.520 align:middle line:84%
They all had the name
of the bank on it.

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:57.007 align:middle line:84%
And the value of the
currency dwindled

00:18:57.007 --> 00:18:58.840 align:middle line:84%
as you got farther and
farther from the bank

00:18:58.840 --> 00:19:00.670 align:middle line:84%
because nobody knew
what it was going

00:19:00.670 --> 00:19:03.520 align:middle line:84%
to be worth by the time you
got to the bank to cash it.

00:19:03.520 --> 00:19:05.586 align:middle line:84%
So it was very
hard for merchants.

00:19:05.586 --> 00:19:06.960 align:middle line:84%
They had catalogs
where you could

00:19:06.960 --> 00:19:08.882 align:middle line:84%
tell which were
the sounder banks

00:19:08.882 --> 00:19:10.840 align:middle line:84%
and what your currency
was allowed to be worth.

00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:12.580 align:middle line:90%
And it was a very unstable--

00:19:12.580 --> 00:19:13.210 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I was
not standardized.

00:19:13.210 --> 00:19:13.709 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:19:13.709 --> 00:19:14.410 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:19:14.410 --> 00:19:18.980 align:middle line:84%
So the national banking
system was put in there

00:19:18.980 --> 00:19:22.680 align:middle line:90%
to try to overcome that.

00:19:22.680 --> 00:19:26.480 align:middle line:84%
The banks would then
deposit some gold

00:19:26.480 --> 00:19:29.010 align:middle line:84%
with the Treasury,
the US Treasury.

00:19:29.010 --> 00:19:31.480 align:middle line:84%
And then they were allowed
to use these bank notes,

00:19:31.480 --> 00:19:32.597 align:middle line:90%
issue these bank notes.

00:19:32.597 --> 00:19:34.930 align:middle line:84%
So it was a good idea for the
banks, the national banks,

00:19:34.930 --> 00:19:36.760 align:middle line:84%
because they still
had their gold.

00:19:36.760 --> 00:19:39.871 align:middle line:84%
But meanwhile they got to print
these notes with their names

00:19:39.871 --> 00:19:40.370 align:middle line:90%
on them.

00:19:40.370 --> 00:19:43.170 align:middle line:84%
But they said "National
Bank" at the top.

00:19:43.170 --> 00:19:45.360 align:middle line:84%
But a dollar was
then worth a dollar.

00:19:45.360 --> 00:19:48.700 align:middle line:84%
That did standardize the
value of the currency.

00:19:48.700 --> 00:19:52.550 align:middle line:84%
But they also taxed the
local banks-- or sorry,

00:19:52.550 --> 00:19:56.080 align:middle line:90%
the state banks' bank notes.

00:19:56.080 --> 00:19:58.450 align:middle line:84%
And the idea was to
try to get everybody

00:19:58.450 --> 00:19:59.390 align:middle line:90%
to be a national bank.

00:19:59.390 --> 00:20:04.160 align:middle line:84%
But the state banks, rather
than succumbing to the ta--

00:20:04.160 --> 00:20:06.850 align:middle line:84%
rather than becoming
national banks,

00:20:06.850 --> 00:20:10.410 align:middle line:84%
that was the beginning of the
whole check cashing system,

00:20:10.410 --> 00:20:13.550 align:middle line:84%
the depository system, where
they didn't use banknotes

00:20:13.550 --> 00:20:14.050 align:middle line:90%
anymore.

00:20:14.050 --> 00:20:16.940 align:middle line:84%
They were just issuing
credits that you would just

00:20:16.940 --> 00:20:18.030 align:middle line:90%
write into an account.

00:20:18.030 --> 00:20:19.930 align:middle line:84%
You would write it
in into as a deposit.

00:20:19.930 --> 00:20:21.250 align:middle line:90%
And that was very unstable.

00:20:21.250 --> 00:20:23.450 align:middle line:84%
So you had runs
on the bank again

00:20:23.450 --> 00:20:25.610 align:middle line:84%
because they would
issue many times more

00:20:25.610 --> 00:20:28.300 align:middle line:84%
credit than they
had gold to back it.

00:20:28.300 --> 00:20:30.859 align:middle line:90%
So that went right up to 1913.

00:20:30.859 --> 00:20:33.150 align:middle line:84%
And the Federal Reserve was
supposed to stabilize that.

00:20:33.150 --> 00:20:35.441 align:middle line:84%
But obviously it didn't,
because we had the biggest run

00:20:35.441 --> 00:20:40.380 align:middle line:90%
ever in 1929, 1933, that period.

00:20:40.380 --> 00:20:41.880 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Let me
ask you a question.

00:20:41.880 --> 00:20:44.090 align:middle line:84%
Now we're up to
the establishment

00:20:44.090 --> 00:20:46.690 align:middle line:84%
of the Federal Reserve, which
is not federal, of course.

00:20:46.690 --> 00:20:49.420 align:middle line:84%
It's a group of men
sitting around a table,

00:20:49.420 --> 00:20:50.740 align:middle line:90%
a group of bankers.

00:20:50.740 --> 00:20:55.530 align:middle line:84%
And up to that time, at several
points in this conversation,

00:20:55.530 --> 00:20:59.880 align:middle line:84%
I'm essentially hearing you
say that the governments,

00:20:59.880 --> 00:21:01.830 align:middle line:84%
local and otherwise,
were actually

00:21:01.830 --> 00:21:06.050 align:middle line:84%
trying to put some kind of
control into the situation.

00:21:06.050 --> 00:21:09.170 align:middle line:84%
And it seems like over
and over the matter

00:21:09.170 --> 00:21:12.720 align:middle line:84%
of money kept defaulting
back into these same hands,

00:21:12.720 --> 00:21:14.220 align:middle line:90%
the banking hands.

00:21:14.220 --> 00:21:17.980 align:middle line:84%
So it's not as though the
government was necessarily

00:21:17.980 --> 00:21:19.960 align:middle line:84%
complicit and evil
in any of this.

00:21:19.960 --> 00:21:21.910 align:middle line:84%
Oftentimes they were
very much looking out

00:21:21.910 --> 00:21:23.825 align:middle line:84%
after the interest
of the people.

00:21:23.825 --> 00:21:26.000 align:middle line:84%
But that's not the
way it is today.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:29.640 align:middle line:84%
It seems to have been
totally co-opted into what

00:21:29.640 --> 00:21:31.410 align:middle line:84%
John Perkins calls a
corporatocracy, where

00:21:31.410 --> 00:21:34.200 align:middle line:84%
the banks run the
government now completely.

00:21:34.200 --> 00:21:37.800 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about the
roots of that beginning,

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:41.850 align:middle line:84%
beginning with the founding
of the Federal Reserve.

00:21:41.850 --> 00:21:44.470 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: The Federal
Reserve was set up

00:21:44.470 --> 00:21:47.130 align:middle line:84%
by some international
bankers, big bankers.

00:21:47.130 --> 00:21:50.700 align:middle line:84%
So it was Rockefeller, Morgan,
who were normally rivals.

00:21:50.700 --> 00:21:53.290 align:middle line:84%
But for the purpose of
this, they got together.

00:21:53.290 --> 00:22:01.290 align:middle line:84%
And it was in response to a
big banking crisis in 1907,

00:22:01.290 --> 00:22:05.710 align:middle line:84%
which rumor has it that Morgan
actually instigated himself

00:22:05.710 --> 00:22:10.220 align:middle line:84%
in order to-- they wanted
to set up this system, where

00:22:10.220 --> 00:22:13.690 align:middle line:84%
originally the Federal
Reserve printed the money

00:22:13.690 --> 00:22:17.250 align:middle line:84%
and lent it to the government
and charged interest on it.

00:22:17.250 --> 00:22:21.670 align:middle line:84%
So that was the deal
that later, in the 1960s,

00:22:21.670 --> 00:22:25.145 align:middle line:84%
that Wright Patman got all over
and said no, this is not fair,

00:22:25.145 --> 00:22:26.520 align:middle line:84%
and tried to get
it nationalized.

00:22:26.520 --> 00:22:28.560 align:middle line:84%
It should have--
everybody thought--

00:22:28.560 --> 00:22:32.580 align:middle line:84%
The opposition thought in
1913 that it was nationalized.

00:22:32.580 --> 00:22:34.560 align:middle line:84%
That was-- William
Jennings Bryan

00:22:34.560 --> 00:22:36.480 align:middle line:84%
was the leader of
the opposition.

00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:39.710 align:middle line:84%
Before that, he had been
the populist candidate

00:22:39.710 --> 00:22:43.580 align:middle line:84%
for a more nationalized
system, for a system where

00:22:43.580 --> 00:22:46.650 align:middle line:84%
the government actually
would issue the money.

00:22:46.650 --> 00:22:48.300 align:middle line:90%
And he said absolutely not.

00:22:48.300 --> 00:22:53.630 align:middle line:84%
There was no way he would
endorse a system where

00:22:53.630 --> 00:22:56.230 align:middle line:84%
private bankers would
be issuing the money

00:22:56.230 --> 00:22:58.120 align:middle line:90%
and charging us interest on it.

00:22:58.120 --> 00:23:00.590 align:middle line:84%
So they changed the name
from the Aldrich Act

00:23:00.590 --> 00:23:02.900 align:middle line:84%
to the Federal Reserve
Act, made it look federal.

00:23:02.900 --> 00:23:04.526 align:middle line:90%
And the language is so obscure.

00:23:04.526 --> 00:23:05.650 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it's still obscure.

00:23:05.650 --> 00:23:08.170 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It's so obscure
that almost nobody knows.

00:23:08.170 --> 00:23:10.760 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's shocking to
me how few people actually

00:23:10.760 --> 00:23:14.060 align:middle line:84%
know the Federal Reserve
is nothing federal at all.

00:23:14.060 --> 00:23:15.740 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: And it's
very hard to read.

00:23:15.740 --> 00:23:16.710 align:middle line:90%
I mean I've read it.

00:23:16.710 --> 00:23:17.940 align:middle line:90%
It's not all that long.

00:23:17.940 --> 00:23:21.370 align:middle line:84%
But it is very
hard to understand,

00:23:21.370 --> 00:23:22.440 align:middle line:90%
certain parts of it--

00:23:22.440 --> 00:23:23.060 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And
you're an attorney.

00:23:23.060 --> 00:23:24.976 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: --exactly what
they're talking about.

00:23:24.976 --> 00:23:25.646 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:23:25.646 --> 00:23:26.270 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:23:26.270 --> 00:23:26.770 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:23:26.770 --> 00:23:27.850 align:middle line:90%
So we have that.

00:23:27.850 --> 00:23:29.780 align:middle line:84%
And then let's talk
about the gold standard.

00:23:29.780 --> 00:23:31.571 align:middle line:84%
I know you have a
completely different view

00:23:31.571 --> 00:23:33.490 align:middle line:84%
about the gold standard
than some people have

00:23:33.490 --> 00:23:35.410 align:middle line:90%
in terms of backing currencies.

00:23:35.410 --> 00:23:37.990 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about when we
went on the gold standard,

00:23:37.990 --> 00:23:40.730 align:middle line:84%
off the gold standard,
and in your mind what

00:23:40.730 --> 00:23:43.544 align:middle line:84%
has happened to us as a result,
at least the currencies.

00:23:43.544 --> 00:23:45.460 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Well, we've
been on the gold standard

00:23:45.460 --> 00:23:50.680 align:middle line:84%
ever since-- the Bank
of England came into--

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:53.000 align:middle line:84%
was chartered in
1694, so that was

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:59.080 align:middle line:84%
three years after the beginning
of the American colonists'

00:23:59.080 --> 00:24:01.610 align:middle line:84%
system of issuing
their own paper money.

00:24:01.610 --> 00:24:05.980 align:middle line:84%
So the Bank of England
is a privately owned--

00:24:05.980 --> 00:24:08.090 align:middle line:84%
or it was then a
privately owned bank.

00:24:08.090 --> 00:24:12.030 align:middle line:84%
It was actually nationalized
in 1946 but in name only.

00:24:12.030 --> 00:24:14.160 align:middle line:90%
It's still the same.

00:24:14.160 --> 00:24:15.980 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, that's
more complicated.

00:24:15.980 --> 00:24:22.190 align:middle line:84%
But so the Bank
of England-- well,

00:24:22.190 --> 00:24:26.360 align:middle line:84%
the king was fighting a war,
and he needed to borrow money.

00:24:26.360 --> 00:24:29.110 align:middle line:84%
And so the Bank of
England was allowed

00:24:29.110 --> 00:24:32.750 align:middle line:84%
to set up as the king's
bank, basically, that

00:24:32.750 --> 00:24:37.840 align:middle line:84%
would lend to the king
and the debt never

00:24:37.840 --> 00:24:39.260 align:middle line:90%
actually had to be paid back.

00:24:39.260 --> 00:24:41.662 align:middle line:84%
It would just keep rolling
over from year to year.

00:24:41.662 --> 00:24:43.620 align:middle line:84%
And all you really had
to pay was the interest.

00:24:43.620 --> 00:24:45.036 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that's
what we have today.

00:24:45.036 --> 00:24:49.870 align:middle line:84%
We have a $15 trillion debt
that just keeps increasing.

00:24:49.870 --> 00:24:51.950 align:middle line:84%
Everybody freaks out over
that, but it's actually

00:24:51.950 --> 00:24:55.190 align:middle line:84%
perfectly fine, because
we have a $15 trillion

00:24:55.190 --> 00:24:56.270 align:middle line:90%
dollar money supply.

00:24:56.270 --> 00:24:59.630 align:middle line:84%
In fact, the federal
debt is our money supply.

00:24:59.630 --> 00:25:01.575 align:middle line:84%
And it's only the interest
that's the problem.

00:25:01.575 --> 00:25:02.370 align:middle line:90%
And that's the thing.

00:25:02.370 --> 00:25:03.590 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: In the
second part, we're

00:25:03.590 --> 00:25:05.420 align:middle line:84%
going to get into this a
little more because most

00:25:05.420 --> 00:25:07.420 align:middle line:84%
people-- you're going to
have to break this down

00:25:07.420 --> 00:25:11.026 align:middle line:90%
into second grader terms for us.

00:25:11.026 --> 00:25:12.900 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: OK, so now I've
forgotten what the--

00:25:12.900 --> 00:25:15.220 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So you were talking
about the establishment

00:25:15.220 --> 00:25:16.279 align:middle line:90%
of the gold--

00:25:16.279 --> 00:25:17.070 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Oh, right.

00:25:17.070 --> 00:25:19.370 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Currency of the
king and the borrowing

00:25:19.370 --> 00:25:21.721 align:middle line:90%
from the banking family.

00:25:21.721 --> 00:25:22.220 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: OK.

00:25:22.220 --> 00:25:26.900 align:middle line:84%
So the Bank of England was
gold-based, theoretically.

00:25:26.900 --> 00:25:29.990 align:middle line:84%
Theoretically you could redeem
these bank notes for gold,

00:25:29.990 --> 00:25:31.120 align:middle line:90%
the government could.

00:25:31.120 --> 00:25:34.420 align:middle line:84%
But they issued many
times more notes

00:25:34.420 --> 00:25:39.530 align:middle line:84%
than they had gold on the
theory that the depositors only

00:25:39.530 --> 00:25:42.880 align:middle line:84%
came for their gold 10% of
the time on the average.

00:25:42.880 --> 00:25:43.970 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:25:43.970 --> 00:25:47.030 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: But all through
the 19th century,

00:25:47.030 --> 00:25:48.850 align:middle line:84%
you had this problem
where you had

00:25:48.850 --> 00:25:50.820 align:middle line:84%
runs on the banks
and banking crises.

00:25:50.820 --> 00:25:52.900 align:middle line:90%
It didn't work well.

00:25:52.900 --> 00:26:00.960 align:middle line:84%
And then in 1933, Roosevelt took
the US off the gold standard

00:26:00.960 --> 00:26:02.910 align:middle line:90%
because he was forced to.

00:26:02.910 --> 00:26:07.130 align:middle line:84%
Because at that time, the
dollar was 40% backed by gold.

00:26:07.130 --> 00:26:10.790 align:middle line:84%
So that meant that every time--
when you had a run the bank,

00:26:10.790 --> 00:26:15.170 align:middle line:84%
as they did then, when people
rushed into the bank to pull

00:26:15.170 --> 00:26:19.450 align:middle line:84%
out $4 worth of gold, the bank
would have to call $6 worth

00:26:19.450 --> 00:26:21.307 align:middle line:84%
of loans, because
there were actually--

00:26:21.307 --> 00:26:22.140 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: The ratio.

00:26:22.140 --> 00:26:22.490 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:26:22.490 --> 00:26:23.140 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:26:23.140 --> 00:26:26.870 align:middle line:84%
So the money supply was just
collapsing in on itself.

00:26:26.870 --> 00:26:28.850 align:middle line:84%
And that's why
there was no money

00:26:28.850 --> 00:26:33.910 align:middle line:84%
to buy-- there was like
fruit falling on the ground,

00:26:33.910 --> 00:26:36.220 align:middle line:84%
and people were starving,
but there was no money

00:26:36.220 --> 00:26:38.010 align:middle line:84%
to pay for the
workers to pick it.

00:26:38.010 --> 00:26:40.760 align:middle line:84%
And there was no money to
buy the fruit at the market.

00:26:40.760 --> 00:26:43.690 align:middle line:84%
There was just a collapse
in the money supply.

00:26:43.690 --> 00:26:47.600 align:middle line:84%
So Roosevelt took the dollar off
the gold standard domestically.

00:26:47.600 --> 00:26:49.930 align:middle line:84%
But it remained on
the gold standard

00:26:49.930 --> 00:26:53.510 align:middle line:90%
internationally until 1971.

00:26:53.510 --> 00:26:56.346 align:middle line:84%
Nixon had to do the same
thing for the same reason.

00:26:56.346 --> 00:26:57.970 align:middle line:84%
The French cashed in
all their dollars.

00:26:57.970 --> 00:26:59.400 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: See now,
a lot of times

00:26:59.400 --> 00:27:02.560 align:middle line:84%
that is portrayed as quite
a negative or downturn

00:27:02.560 --> 00:27:03.670 align:middle line:90%
of events in the country.

00:27:03.670 --> 00:27:05.724 align:middle line:84%
But you're saying
not necessarily so.

00:27:05.724 --> 00:27:08.140 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to take a little
break for a couple minutes

00:27:08.140 --> 00:27:10.580 align:middle line:84%
so everybody can kind of
shake their brain a bit

00:27:10.580 --> 00:27:12.000 align:middle line:90%
and get ready for Part Two.

