Ellen and I were talking
off camera a bit,

00:27:23.570 --> 00:27:27.350 align:middle line:84%
and there was one part of this
historical piece of the story

00:27:27.350 --> 00:27:29.160 align:middle line:84%
that you didn't have
a chance to address

00:27:29.160 --> 00:27:31.310 align:middle line:84%
that we want to get
into, which was really

00:27:31.310 --> 00:27:32.710 align:middle line:90%
in Benjamin Franklin's time.

00:27:32.710 --> 00:27:35.230 align:middle line:84%
And this had to do with
the colony of Pennsylvania

00:27:35.230 --> 00:27:37.310 align:middle line:84%
and a bank that was
established there.

00:27:37.310 --> 00:27:39.420 align:middle line:84%
And I've heard you talk
about this before and find

00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:40.080 align:middle line:90%
it fascinating.

00:27:40.080 --> 00:27:41.670 align:middle line:84%
So let's go to
that, and then we'll

00:27:41.670 --> 00:27:44.360 align:middle line:84%
go back to this whole
gold standard thing.

00:27:44.360 --> 00:27:46.380 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: OK.

00:27:46.380 --> 00:27:48.830 align:middle line:84%
This was when the colonies
were printing their own money.

00:27:48.830 --> 00:27:50.980 align:middle line:90%
It was all very experimental.

00:27:50.980 --> 00:27:52.950 align:middle line:84%
Nobody knew exactly
what would happen.

00:27:52.950 --> 00:27:57.380 align:middle line:84%
And some colonies did over-print
and hyperinflate the currency,

00:27:57.380 --> 00:27:58.830 align:middle line:90%
devalue the currency.

00:27:58.830 --> 00:28:00.860 align:middle line:10%
But in a few of
the colonies, they

00:28:00.860 --> 00:28:02.460 align:middle line:10%
had a very sustainable system.

00:28:02.460 --> 00:28:05.270 align:middle line:10%
And the ideal, the
one that perfected it,

00:28:05.270 --> 00:28:09.780 align:middle line:10%
was Pennsylvania at the
time that Benjamin Franklin

00:28:09.780 --> 00:28:10.310 align:middle line:10%
was there.

00:28:10.310 --> 00:28:12.360 align:middle line:10%
And he was called the
father of paper money

00:28:12.360 --> 00:28:16.540 align:middle line:10%
because he wrote about it and
popularized this whole system.

00:28:16.540 --> 00:28:18.350 align:middle line:84%
But what the
Pennsylvanians did that was

00:28:18.350 --> 00:28:21.840 align:middle line:84%
different was that, instead
of just printing and spending,

00:28:21.840 --> 00:28:24.020 align:middle line:84%
printing and spending,
the government

00:28:24.020 --> 00:28:27.050 align:middle line:90%
would print and lend the money.

00:28:27.050 --> 00:28:29.190 align:middle line:84%
And it would come back
to the government.

00:28:29.190 --> 00:28:32.620 align:middle line:90%
So it was called the Land Bank.

00:28:32.620 --> 00:28:34.350 align:middle line:84%
It was supposedly
backed by land,

00:28:34.350 --> 00:28:38.270 align:middle line:84%
the farmers would
take out loans,

00:28:38.270 --> 00:28:40.610 align:middle line:84%
and they would put up
their land as collateral.

00:28:40.610 --> 00:28:42.940 align:middle line:84%
Although I guess the land
was never really taken.

00:28:42.940 --> 00:28:45.194 align:middle line:84%
It was just so that they
could back it by something.

00:28:45.194 --> 00:28:46.110 align:middle line:90%
They didn't have gold.

00:28:46.110 --> 00:28:47.235 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: This is by faith.

00:28:47.235 --> 00:28:48.402 align:middle line:90%
Faith is part of the system.

00:28:48.402 --> 00:28:48.985 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:28:48.985 --> 00:28:51.080 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Good faith is
part of a banking system,

00:28:51.080 --> 00:28:54.310 align:middle line:90%
theoretically, yeah.

00:28:54.310 --> 00:28:58.190 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: So say you could print
$105, or whatever they're using

00:28:58.190 --> 00:29:02.550 align:middle line:84%
and then lend $100
at 5% interest

00:29:02.550 --> 00:29:07.050 align:middle line:84%
and then spend $5 on
the government's budget.

00:29:07.050 --> 00:29:09.710 align:middle line:84%
And then you would
have $105 out there

00:29:09.710 --> 00:29:12.380 align:middle line:84%
to come back as
principal and interest.

00:29:12.380 --> 00:29:16.270 align:middle line:84%
And then you could lend
$100 again, spend the $5,

00:29:16.270 --> 00:29:19.320 align:middle line:84%
and $105 would come back
as principal and interest.

00:29:19.320 --> 00:29:21.300 align:middle line:84%
And you could do that
over and over and over,

00:29:21.300 --> 00:29:24.120 align:middle line:84%
and you would never have
to inflate the money supply

00:29:24.120 --> 00:29:25.980 align:middle line:84%
for the purpose of
paying the debt.

00:29:25.980 --> 00:29:29.900 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you could inflate it
if necessary because you're

00:29:29.900 --> 00:29:33.030 align:middle line:84%
productivity increased, and
you needed money out there.

00:29:33.030 --> 00:29:35.510 align:middle line:84%
So during the time that
that system was in place,

00:29:35.510 --> 00:29:38.560 align:middle line:84%
they had no inflation,
price inflation,

00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:40.350 align:middle line:84%
they had no government
debt, obviously,

00:29:40.350 --> 00:29:42.990 align:middle line:84%
because they just
printed the money.

00:29:42.990 --> 00:29:46.315 align:middle line:84%
And something else
good happened.

00:29:46.315 --> 00:29:47.440 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Why did it crash?

00:29:47.440 --> 00:29:49.980 align:middle line:84%
I mean why did
that bank go away?

00:29:49.980 --> 00:29:53.140 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: It was the
King of England.

00:29:53.140 --> 00:29:55.640 align:middle line:84%
Well, the Bank of England
leaned on the king

00:29:55.640 --> 00:29:58.430 align:middle line:84%
to forbid the colonies
to print their own money.

00:29:58.430 --> 00:30:04.000 align:middle line:84%
At first they only forbade
certain colonies-- well,

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.865 align:middle line:84%
it was most of them-- but the
ones that were overprinting.

00:30:06.865 --> 00:30:08.281 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Doing
well without them?

00:30:08.281 --> 00:30:09.490 align:middle line:90%
No. [LAUGHS]

00:30:09.490 --> 00:30:11.310 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: But
Pennsylvania was allowed

00:30:11.310 --> 00:30:12.930 align:middle line:84%
to stay in operation
and some others,

00:30:12.930 --> 00:30:15.250 align:middle line:84%
because they did have
sustainable systems.

00:30:15.250 --> 00:30:18.710 align:middle line:84%
But then Benjamin
Franklin made a mistake

00:30:18.710 --> 00:30:21.280 align:middle line:90%
that others have made since.

00:30:21.280 --> 00:30:24.170 align:middle line:84%
He went to England
and argued the case.

00:30:24.170 --> 00:30:27.865 align:middle line:84%
So he said how well they
were doing and the colonies--

00:30:27.865 --> 00:30:29.907 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: The sleeping
dogs lie principle.

00:30:29.907 --> 00:30:30.990 align:middle line:90%
Should have left it alone.

00:30:30.990 --> 00:30:31.531 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yes.

00:30:31.531 --> 00:30:33.820 align:middle line:84%
So he was trying to argue
that all the colonies should

00:30:33.820 --> 00:30:35.290 align:middle line:84%
be able to print
their own money.

00:30:35.290 --> 00:30:38.650 align:middle line:84%
And he said that before
they were just wilderness,

00:30:38.650 --> 00:30:40.630 align:middle line:84%
and now they were
doing marvelously well.

00:30:40.630 --> 00:30:45.180 align:middle line:84%
And everybody marveled at how
they had been so productive

00:30:45.180 --> 00:30:50.180 align:middle line:84%
considering that they
started out with nothing.

00:30:50.180 --> 00:30:54.000 align:middle line:84%
And so the Bank of
England was not pleased

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:57.440 align:middle line:84%
that the bankers then
leaned on the king

00:30:57.440 --> 00:30:59.900 align:middle line:84%
and the king forbade them
all to issue their own money.

00:30:59.900 --> 00:31:03.950 align:middle line:84%
And that supposedly
was a critical factor

00:31:03.950 --> 00:31:06.630 align:middle line:90%
in the Revolutionary War.

00:31:06.630 --> 00:31:09.300 align:middle line:84%
That then they had a
depression because they

00:31:09.300 --> 00:31:11.790 align:middle line:84%
didn't have enough money
to pay their debts.

00:31:11.790 --> 00:31:13.690 align:middle line:84%
And the farmers were
losing their farms.

00:31:13.690 --> 00:31:16.180 align:middle line:84%
And so they just went
back to printing money,

00:31:16.180 --> 00:31:19.640 align:middle line:84%
which was considered
an act of rebellion.

00:31:19.640 --> 00:31:20.330 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:31:20.330 --> 00:31:25.050 align:middle line:84%
And we can go back to the gold
standard part of the story.

00:31:25.050 --> 00:31:27.890 align:middle line:84%
I mean it's important
just kind of to tidy up

00:31:27.890 --> 00:31:30.040 align:middle line:84%
that piece of what
happened there

00:31:30.040 --> 00:31:33.230 align:middle line:84%
and why now we're even
hearing about currencies that

00:31:33.230 --> 00:31:35.950 align:middle line:84%
are emerging, governments
demanding that we go back

00:31:35.950 --> 00:31:39.280 align:middle line:84%
to some currencies that
are safe and gold-backed.

00:31:39.280 --> 00:31:41.580 align:middle line:84%
But let's tie the historical
piece in with that

00:31:41.580 --> 00:31:43.480 align:middle line:84%
and then make your
comment on that.

00:31:43.480 --> 00:31:44.350 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: OK.

00:31:44.350 --> 00:31:48.850 align:middle line:84%
Well, then in 1971, Nixon
had to do the same thing

00:31:48.850 --> 00:31:52.480 align:middle line:84%
that Roosevelt had done
because it worked fine

00:31:52.480 --> 00:31:55.890 align:middle line:84%
as long as nobody
came for their gold.

00:31:55.890 --> 00:31:59.270 align:middle line:84%
But in the Vietnam War,
we went heavily into debt,

00:31:59.270 --> 00:32:02.070 align:middle line:90%
and DeGaulle could see that.

00:32:02.070 --> 00:32:06.890 align:middle line:84%
And so he called our bluff and
took all his dollars-- traded

00:32:06.890 --> 00:32:10.250 align:middle line:84%
all his dollars in for gold,
which was actually paid.

00:32:10.250 --> 00:32:12.890 align:middle line:84%
But then the British tried
to do the same thing.

00:32:12.890 --> 00:32:16.410 align:middle line:84%
And that would have reduced
our gold supply so much that it

00:32:16.410 --> 00:32:19.120 align:middle line:84%
would have, you know, the
dollar would have collapsed.

00:32:19.120 --> 00:32:19.725 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, valueless.

00:32:19.725 --> 00:32:20.225 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:32:20.225 --> 00:32:23.510 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: And so Nixon took the
dollar off the gold standard.

00:32:23.510 --> 00:32:26.460 align:middle line:90%
So that system doesn't work.

00:32:26.460 --> 00:32:28.090 align:middle line:84%
The other alternative
that people

00:32:28.090 --> 00:32:31.920 align:middle line:84%
talk about when they talk about
our gold standard is 100% gold.

00:32:31.920 --> 00:32:35.601 align:middle line:84%
But that totally won't
work because there's not

00:32:35.601 --> 00:32:36.100 align:middle line:90%
enough gold.

00:32:36.100 --> 00:32:39.260 align:middle line:90%
And it's not fluid enough.

00:32:39.260 --> 00:32:41.610 align:middle line:90%
You need an expandable system.

00:32:41.610 --> 00:32:46.340 align:middle line:84%
Our entire economy
runs on credit.

00:32:46.340 --> 00:32:48.100 align:middle line:84%
It's just like the
small businessman

00:32:48.100 --> 00:32:49.590 align:middle line:84%
that pays his
workers and materials

00:32:49.590 --> 00:32:52.100 align:middle line:90%
before he has a product to sell.

00:32:52.100 --> 00:32:55.100 align:middle line:84%
Well, there's a man
who is a gold proponent

00:32:55.100 --> 00:32:58.270 align:middle line:84%
himself, Antel-- I'm
probably pronouncing his name

00:32:58.270 --> 00:32:58.920 align:middle line:90%
wrong-- Fekete.

00:32:58.920 --> 00:33:03.080 align:middle line:84%
F-E-K-E-T-E. But he's written
extensively about this,

00:33:03.080 --> 00:33:08.010 align:middle line:84%
that it was actually because of
real bills or bills of credit

00:33:08.010 --> 00:33:10.240 align:middle line:84%
that the gold system
worked at all.

00:33:10.240 --> 00:33:13.130 align:middle line:84%
But if you have
all these producers

00:33:13.130 --> 00:33:15.530 align:middle line:84%
at different levels
of production,

00:33:15.530 --> 00:33:17.950 align:middle line:84%
and they all operate
on credit, you

00:33:17.950 --> 00:33:20.110 align:middle line:84%
would have to-- the
way he calculated it,

00:33:20.110 --> 00:33:24.380 align:middle line:84%
he gave an example of a drug
that had 90 different producers

00:33:24.380 --> 00:33:26.460 align:middle line:84%
before the drug
made it to market.

00:33:26.460 --> 00:33:31.360 align:middle line:84%
It will cost $5,000 in credit
just to make a $100 product.

00:33:31.360 --> 00:33:36.560 align:middle line:84%
I mean that many loans are taken
out to make this end product.

00:33:36.560 --> 00:33:38.690 align:middle line:84%
So you're going to
have to find people

00:33:38.690 --> 00:33:42.660 align:middle line:84%
willing to lend their
$5,000 worth of gold just

00:33:42.660 --> 00:33:45.320 align:middle line:90%
to make all these products.

00:33:45.320 --> 00:33:47.850 align:middle line:84%
And the whole system
will choke when

00:33:47.850 --> 00:33:49.420 align:middle line:90%
you can't find those people.

00:33:49.420 --> 00:33:50.880 align:middle line:90%
And that's what we see in--

00:33:50.880 --> 00:33:52.504 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: What if,
theoretically, there

00:33:52.504 --> 00:33:55.100 align:middle line:84%
were enough gold to do
100% gold-backed currency.

00:33:55.100 --> 00:33:57.250 align:middle line:90%
What if that were the case?

00:33:57.250 --> 00:34:00.010 align:middle line:90%
Could it work?

00:34:00.010 --> 00:34:02.324 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Well, if all
the gold were out there--

00:34:02.324 --> 00:34:04.490 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you have to have
an expandable money supply.

00:34:04.490 --> 00:34:05.198 align:middle line:90%
That's the point.

00:34:05.198 --> 00:34:08.879 align:middle line:84%
You can't start with a fixed
supply and keep it that way.

00:34:08.879 --> 00:34:10.170 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No matter what it is.

00:34:10.170 --> 00:34:10.570 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:10.570 --> 00:34:12.611 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: As long as you
have a debt-based system,

00:34:12.611 --> 00:34:14.960 align:middle line:84%
because you've got to
keep expanding just

00:34:14.960 --> 00:34:16.239 align:middle line:90%
to cover the debt.

00:34:16.239 --> 00:34:20.440 align:middle line:84%
And we see that in the
Eurozone, where they've

00:34:20.440 --> 00:34:23.830 align:middle line:84%
attempted to use a
fixed amount of euros.

00:34:23.830 --> 00:34:25.700 align:middle line:84%
And what happened was
everybody's in debt.

00:34:25.700 --> 00:34:27.719 align:middle line:84%
So they're all trying to
borrow from each other.

00:34:27.719 --> 00:34:29.550 align:middle line:84%
But they're all
going down together.

00:34:29.550 --> 00:34:32.010 align:middle line:84%
And the only way
they're managing

00:34:32.010 --> 00:34:35.650 align:middle line:84%
to pull out of it at all it
is that the European Central

00:34:35.650 --> 00:34:39.500 align:middle line:84%
Bank has now agreed
to print and lend

00:34:39.500 --> 00:34:42.330 align:middle line:84%
to the governments,
something that's

00:34:42.330 --> 00:34:45.020 align:middle line:84%
a violation of their
original rules.

00:34:45.020 --> 00:34:46.550 align:middle line:90%
But I mean they have to do it.

00:34:46.550 --> 00:34:48.420 align:middle line:84%
First they were
lending to the banks.

00:34:48.420 --> 00:34:50.760 align:middle line:84%
That just started
like last January.

00:34:50.760 --> 00:34:54.170 align:middle line:84%
And now they're actually
going to lend to--

00:34:54.170 --> 00:34:56.600 align:middle line:84%
with this new European
stability mechanism.

00:34:56.600 --> 00:34:59.135 align:middle line:90%


00:34:59.135 --> 00:34:59.760 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:34:59.760 --> 00:35:01.776 align:middle line:84%
OK, well let's talk about
the state-owned bank.

00:35:01.776 --> 00:35:03.400 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about some
of the solutions,

00:35:03.400 --> 00:35:06.394 align:middle line:84%
then, because we looked at
Pennsylvania a moment ago.

00:35:06.394 --> 00:35:08.060 align:middle line:84%
And you said that was
actually something

00:35:08.060 --> 00:35:09.900 align:middle line:90%
that was quite viable.

00:35:09.900 --> 00:35:12.920 align:middle line:10%
But in more modern times,
we have a renegade state,

00:35:12.920 --> 00:35:15.270 align:middle line:10%
the state of North
Dakota, which decided

00:35:15.270 --> 00:35:17.910 align:middle line:10%
to take this upon themselves.

00:35:17.910 --> 00:35:20.870 align:middle line:10%
And they established the
Bank of North Dakota.

00:35:20.870 --> 00:35:23.910 align:middle line:10%
Let's talk about it, in really
plain, simple, kindergarten

00:35:23.910 --> 00:35:26.290 align:middle line:10%
terms, how that works,
why it's working,

00:35:26.290 --> 00:35:29.330 align:middle line:10%
what has happened to the
people in North Dakota,

00:35:29.330 --> 00:35:32.420 align:middle line:10%
their economic system,
compared to everybody else

00:35:32.420 --> 00:35:36.840 align:middle line:10%
during this whole downturn
since 2008 in particular.

00:35:36.840 --> 00:35:39.520 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: The North
Dakotans in 1919

00:35:39.520 --> 00:35:41.820 align:middle line:84%
set up their own bank,
the Bank of North Dakota.

00:35:41.820 --> 00:35:45.070 align:middle line:84%
And this is because the
farmers were losing their farms

00:35:45.070 --> 00:35:46.370 align:middle line:90%
to the Wall Street bankers.

00:35:46.370 --> 00:35:48.570 align:middle line:84%
And when they
realized that, they

00:35:48.570 --> 00:35:50.780 align:middle line:84%
decided they wanted to
keep their money local

00:35:50.780 --> 00:35:53.920 align:middle line:84%
and use their credit
for their own purposes.

00:35:53.920 --> 00:35:56.700 align:middle line:84%
So it was the
nonpartisan league.

00:35:56.700 --> 00:35:59.790 align:middle line:84%
It was neither
Republican nor Democrat.

00:35:59.790 --> 00:36:01.660 align:middle line:90%
It was not about politics.

00:36:01.660 --> 00:36:04.965 align:middle line:84%
It was about the local ec--
it was local-- it was about--

00:36:04.965 --> 00:36:06.340 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Their
own preservation.

00:36:06.340 --> 00:36:06.923 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:36:06.923 --> 00:36:07.970 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:36:07.970 --> 00:36:09.990 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: And they had
a very fiery leader

00:36:09.990 --> 00:36:12.700 align:middle line:90%
who did great speeches.

00:36:12.700 --> 00:36:16.500 align:middle line:84%
And so they managed to set
up this bank, which has now

00:36:16.500 --> 00:36:20.000 align:middle line:84%
been in operation for 93
years or something like that

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:26.610 align:middle line:84%
and has fought all
the-- the Supreme Court.

00:36:26.610 --> 00:36:28.600 align:middle line:84%
They've gone through
everything, and they've

00:36:28.600 --> 00:36:33.570 align:middle line:84%
got a very stable bank now,
which is very profitable.

00:36:33.570 --> 00:36:38.040 align:middle line:84%
It's returned I think $300
million in the last decade

00:36:38.040 --> 00:36:41.980 align:middle line:84%
to the state government, which
doesn't sound like a lot,

00:36:41.980 --> 00:36:46.524 align:middle line:84%
but North Dakota is 1/18 the
size of Los Angeles County.

00:36:46.524 --> 00:36:47.190 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:36:47.190 --> 00:36:49.477 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's all
a relative scale.

00:36:49.477 --> 00:36:50.060 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:36:50.060 --> 00:36:51.580 align:middle line:84%
It's really the
size of a county,

00:36:51.580 --> 00:36:56.320 align:middle line:84%
of a modest-sized
county, not LA County.

00:36:56.320 --> 00:36:59.120 align:middle line:84%
So that's actually a lot
of money for their system.

00:36:59.120 --> 00:37:01.950 align:middle line:84%
They've returned almost
as much as the oil

00:37:01.950 --> 00:37:05.050 align:middle line:90%
industry has returned in taxes.

00:37:05.050 --> 00:37:09.660 align:middle line:84%
And so the beauty
of the bank-- they

00:37:09.660 --> 00:37:13.280 align:middle line:84%
did not suffer from
the credit crisis.

00:37:13.280 --> 00:37:17.990 align:middle line:84%
The state has had a very nice
surplus every year since 2008.

00:37:17.990 --> 00:37:19.365 align:middle line:84%
They have the
lowest default rate

00:37:19.365 --> 00:37:23.310 align:middle line:84%
in the country, the lowest
unemployment rate, the lowest

00:37:23.310 --> 00:37:26.320 align:middle line:90%
foreclosure rate.

00:37:26.320 --> 00:37:31.320 align:middle line:84%
The Bank of North Dakota
partners with the local banks,

00:37:31.320 --> 00:37:34.290 align:middle line:84%
so it allows the local banks
to make loans that they just

00:37:34.290 --> 00:37:35.640 align:middle line:90%
otherwise couldn't.

00:37:35.640 --> 00:37:38.440 align:middle line:84%
It's a way of getting around
this capital requirement, which

00:37:38.440 --> 00:37:40.580 align:middle line:84%
is imposed from
abroad and I would

00:37:40.580 --> 00:37:43.771 align:middle line:90%
argue is designed to keep a--

00:37:43.771 --> 00:37:45.020 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Keep a stranglehold.

00:37:45.020 --> 00:37:46.609 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah, exactly.

00:37:46.609 --> 00:37:47.150 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:37:47.150 --> 00:37:50.870 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about if we were--
let's talk about the state

00:37:50.870 --> 00:37:55.080 align:middle line:84%
of California, now the seventh
largest economy in the world,

00:37:55.080 --> 00:37:59.430 align:middle line:84%
and establishing a state-owned
bank; how that would work

00:37:59.430 --> 00:38:02.310 align:middle line:84%
once it's established;
what is given

00:38:02.310 --> 00:38:06.890 align:middle line:84%
back by way of infrastructure,
services to the people,

00:38:06.890 --> 00:38:10.230 align:middle line:84%
and so forth; and, again, in
kindergarten terms for us.

00:38:10.230 --> 00:38:11.180 align:middle line:90%
How would we do this?

00:38:11.180 --> 00:38:13.640 align:middle line:84%
Because you're a big proponent
of state-owned banks.

00:38:13.640 --> 00:38:15.970 align:middle line:84%
How do you do it with
something as unwieldy

00:38:15.970 --> 00:38:17.710 align:middle line:90%
as the state of California?

00:38:17.710 --> 00:38:18.640 align:middle line:90%
What's that look like?

00:38:18.640 --> 00:38:20.931 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Well, it would look
pretty good in California,

00:38:20.931 --> 00:38:23.330 align:middle line:84%
I think, because California
has a huge amount of assets.

00:38:23.330 --> 00:38:24.288 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Boy, does it.

00:38:24.288 --> 00:38:29.006 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: We have $70 billion
in a treasurer's pool that's

00:38:29.006 --> 00:38:30.380 align:middle line:84%
just sitting there
doing nothing.

00:38:30.380 --> 00:38:31.546 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: But wait a minute.

00:38:31.546 --> 00:38:33.050 align:middle line:90%
They argue the state's broke.

00:38:33.050 --> 00:38:34.400 align:middle line:90%
They're shutting down parks.

00:38:34.400 --> 00:38:35.382 align:middle line:90%
What do you mean?

00:38:35.382 --> 00:38:35.882 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:38:35.882 --> 00:38:36.600 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: [LAUGHS]

00:38:36.600 --> 00:38:37.900 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Tell us
the truth about that.

00:38:37.900 --> 00:38:38.120 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:38:38.120 --> 00:38:39.110 align:middle line:90%
People don't know this.

00:38:39.110 --> 00:38:43.860 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Well, there
are all these agencies

00:38:43.860 --> 00:38:47.230 align:middle line:84%
and local governments that
have-- all their extra money

00:38:47.230 --> 00:38:50.850 align:middle line:84%
is put into funds, which are in
the nature of rainy day funds.

00:38:50.850 --> 00:38:53.500 align:middle line:84%
But they don't want to share
with each other necessarily,

00:38:53.500 --> 00:38:56.370 align:middle line:84%
and they don't want to give
it back to the general fund.

00:38:56.370 --> 00:38:59.870 align:middle line:84%
And whenever the
governor has tried

00:38:59.870 --> 00:39:02.650 align:middle line:84%
to get the money
to pay the budget,

00:39:02.650 --> 00:39:05.120 align:middle line:84%
then-- well I know
there was a case where

00:39:05.120 --> 00:39:07.500 align:middle line:84%
they tried to get-- Governor
Schwarzenegger tried

00:39:07.500 --> 00:39:10.570 align:middle line:90%
to get the highway fund money.

00:39:10.570 --> 00:39:12.020 align:middle line:90%
And somebody took him to court.

00:39:12.020 --> 00:39:15.060 align:middle line:84%
And the court said, no,
that this was for highways.

00:39:15.060 --> 00:39:17.620 align:middle line:84%
It was earmarked for
highways, and you

00:39:17.620 --> 00:39:21.520 align:middle line:90%
couldn't use it for your budget.

00:39:21.520 --> 00:39:23.350 align:middle line:84%
So all that money is
just sitting there.

00:39:23.350 --> 00:39:25.880 align:middle line:84%
Right now it's in
a treasurer's pool.

00:39:25.880 --> 00:39:28.130 align:middle line:84%
There's other money
besides this $70 billion.

00:39:28.130 --> 00:39:33.380 align:middle line:84%
But those agencies that want
to use the treasurer's pool,

00:39:33.380 --> 00:39:35.640 align:middle line:90%
that money is $70 billion.

00:39:35.640 --> 00:39:38.690 align:middle line:90%
It's earning 0.49% right now.

00:39:38.690 --> 00:39:40.630 align:middle line:90%
So it's earning almost nothing.

00:39:40.630 --> 00:39:41.800 align:middle line:90%
And it never gets spent.

00:39:41.800 --> 00:39:43.900 align:middle line:84%
You can look at a chart
of this whole fund,

00:39:43.900 --> 00:39:46.150 align:middle line:84%
and it's done nothing
in the last 10 years.

00:39:46.150 --> 00:39:48.733 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: If someone wanted to
take it on and do some research

00:39:48.733 --> 00:39:51.610 align:middle line:84%
and look it up, what do
they do a Google search on?

00:39:51.610 --> 00:39:53.680 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: You can look at
the treasurer's website.

00:39:53.680 --> 00:39:54.270 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK

00:39:54.270 --> 00:39:56.760 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: And he's
got it in there.

00:39:56.760 --> 00:39:59.147 align:middle line:84%
It's called the Treasurer's
Investment Pool.

00:39:59.147 --> 00:40:00.730 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Treasurer's
Investment Pool.

00:40:00.730 --> 00:40:04.190 align:middle line:84%
So there's a $70,000
of money sitting there.

00:40:04.190 --> 00:40:05.190 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: $70 billion.

00:40:05.190 --> 00:40:06.648 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: $70
billion sitting there

00:40:06.648 --> 00:40:08.330 align:middle line:84%
that's not being
utilized at this time

00:40:08.330 --> 00:40:12.120 align:middle line:84%
while they argue with each
other every summer about all

00:40:12.120 --> 00:40:15.020 align:middle line:84%
the shortfalls and which
programs are going to be axed.

00:40:15.020 --> 00:40:17.470 align:middle line:84%
And education
takes the first hit

00:40:17.470 --> 00:40:19.480 align:middle line:90%
usually, and on and on and on.

00:40:19.480 --> 00:40:23.647 align:middle line:84%
I mean that seems rather
immoral, to say the least.

00:40:23.647 --> 00:40:25.480 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: But how do you
get around this rule

00:40:25.480 --> 00:40:28.780 align:middle line:84%
that you can't spend
that rainy day money?

00:40:28.780 --> 00:40:30.940 align:middle line:84%
In North Dakota,
that money would all

00:40:30.940 --> 00:40:34.090 align:middle line:84%
be deposited in the
Bank of North Dakota.

00:40:34.090 --> 00:40:37.650 align:middle line:84%
So what a bank could do
that nobody else can do,

00:40:37.650 --> 00:40:39.710 align:middle line:84%
what a charter bank
is allowed to do,

00:40:39.710 --> 00:40:42.860 align:middle line:84%
is to lend their money, even
though it's still in deposit.

00:40:42.860 --> 00:40:44.710 align:middle line:84%
So they basically
double the money.

00:40:44.710 --> 00:40:46.369 align:middle line:84%
So you could take
that $70 billion.

00:40:46.369 --> 00:40:47.410 align:middle line:90%
It's still sitting there.

00:40:47.410 --> 00:40:50.650 align:middle line:90%
You could still pay them 0.49%.

00:40:50.650 --> 00:40:52.274 align:middle line:84%
You could pay them
more than that.

00:40:52.274 --> 00:40:54.690 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And they become a
depositor into the state bank.

00:40:54.690 --> 00:40:57.489 align:middle line:84%
All those accounts, those pools,
are deposited into state bank?

00:40:57.489 --> 00:40:58.030 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Mhm.

00:40:58.030 --> 00:40:58.571 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:40:58.571 --> 00:41:00.280 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: And then,
well, ideally you

00:41:00.280 --> 00:41:02.280 align:middle line:84%
would use a little for
your capital requirement,

00:41:02.280 --> 00:41:05.300 align:middle line:84%
but there are other ways to
raise the capital if there's

00:41:05.300 --> 00:41:06.280 align:middle line:90%
some objection to that.

00:41:06.280 --> 00:41:07.640 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, but we're just
doing the kindergarten version.

00:41:07.640 --> 00:41:08.300 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: OK.

00:41:08.300 --> 00:41:08.800 align:middle line:90%
So

00:41:08.800 --> 00:41:10.235 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: We can understand it.

00:41:10.235 --> 00:41:10.860 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Right.

00:41:10.860 --> 00:41:15.340 align:middle line:84%
You take your $70
billion and lend it.

00:41:15.340 --> 00:41:18.950 align:middle line:84%
One thing you could do is to
just buy plain old government

00:41:18.950 --> 00:41:20.990 align:middle line:90%
bonds.

00:41:20.990 --> 00:41:23.050 align:middle line:84%
You know how when
they do infrastructure

00:41:23.050 --> 00:41:24.410 align:middle line:90%
they issue these bonds?

00:41:24.410 --> 00:41:24.642 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Bonds.

00:41:24.642 --> 00:41:24.760 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:41:24.760 --> 00:41:25.343 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:41:25.343 --> 00:41:27.330 align:middle line:84%
And that's how they
fund the infrastructure.

00:41:27.330 --> 00:41:32.810 align:middle line:84%
So we are paying-- I
think in California

00:41:32.810 --> 00:41:36.230 align:middle line:84%
the outstanding revenue
infrastructure type bonds is

00:41:36.230 --> 00:41:39.420 align:middle line:90%
$155 billion in debt right now.

00:41:39.420 --> 00:41:43.050 align:middle line:84%
Of that, $70 billion
was interest.

00:41:43.050 --> 00:41:47.380 align:middle line:84%
So if you had funded your own
bonds through your own bank,

00:41:47.380 --> 00:41:49.670 align:middle line:84%
if the government had,
we would be $70 billion

00:41:49.670 --> 00:41:52.160 align:middle line:90%
richer in California now.

00:41:52.160 --> 00:41:55.360 align:middle line:84%
So that's one simple way to
do it is just buy the bonds,

00:41:55.360 --> 00:41:56.892 align:middle line:90%
fund your own bonds instead of--

00:41:56.892 --> 00:41:58.100 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: From your own bank.

00:41:58.100 --> 00:41:59.683 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: --instead
of putting yourself

00:41:59.683 --> 00:42:04.260 align:middle line:84%
at the mercy of this very
voracious bond market, where

00:42:04.260 --> 00:42:08.960 align:middle line:84%
you have to get interest rate
swaps, which is what has broken

00:42:08.960 --> 00:42:12.430 align:middle line:84%
Oakland and other cities that
have fallen for this Wall

00:42:12.430 --> 00:42:14.780 align:middle line:90%
Street scam.

00:42:14.780 --> 00:42:16.340 align:middle line:84%
So if you just lend
to yourself, you

00:42:16.340 --> 00:42:18.890 align:middle line:84%
can eliminate the interest,
which is 35-- well,

00:42:18.890 --> 00:42:23.840 align:middle line:84%
it's actually 40% of public
projects is interest.

00:42:23.840 --> 00:42:25.950 align:middle line:84%
Or you could partner
with the local banks,

00:42:25.950 --> 00:42:29.630 align:middle line:84%
like they do in North Dakota,
and expand the lending

00:42:29.630 --> 00:42:31.680 align:middle line:90%
possibility of the local banks.

00:42:31.680 --> 00:42:35.430 align:middle line:84%
So my friend who is
now paying 16% interest

00:42:35.430 --> 00:42:37.030 align:middle line:90%
could be paying the 8%.

00:42:37.030 --> 00:42:38.960 align:middle line:84%
He could have his
credit line again.

00:42:38.960 --> 00:42:41.480 align:middle line:84%
They would have
that-- the wherewithal

00:42:41.480 --> 00:42:43.640 align:middle line:84%
to make the loans
it used to make.

00:42:43.640 --> 00:42:45.697 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Let's
talk about Japan.

00:42:45.697 --> 00:42:47.530 align:middle line:84%
I heard you in an
interview recently talking

00:42:47.530 --> 00:42:50.610 align:middle line:84%
about what Japan has been
doing and the way in which they

00:42:50.610 --> 00:42:54.290 align:middle line:84%
interface with this subject,
which has some similarities.

00:42:54.290 --> 00:42:55.640 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:42:55.640 --> 00:43:00.390 align:middle line:84%
Japan is considered-- they have
the worst debt-to-GDP ratio

00:43:00.390 --> 00:43:03.000 align:middle line:84%
of any major country
in the world.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:06.210 align:middle line:84%
And everybody thinks,
oh, the poor Japanese.

00:43:06.210 --> 00:43:14.480 align:middle line:84%
I think they have something
like 220% of the GDP is debt.

00:43:14.480 --> 00:43:17.900 align:middle line:84%
But in fact, the debt
is to themselves.

00:43:17.900 --> 00:43:20.000 align:middle line:84%
They have borrowed from
their own central bank

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:23.340 align:middle line:84%
and from their own
Japan Post Bank, which

00:43:23.340 --> 00:43:24.977 align:middle line:90%
is a government-owned bank.

00:43:24.977 --> 00:43:26.060 align:middle line:90%
Japan Post Bank is where--

00:43:26.060 --> 00:43:28.140 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Which is like aligned
with the postal service?

00:43:28.140 --> 00:43:28.723 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:43:28.723 --> 00:43:29.790 align:middle line:90%
It is the postal service.

00:43:29.790 --> 00:43:32.000 align:middle line:84%
But they also have
banking services.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:34.990 align:middle line:84%
And it's where the people
deposit their money.

00:43:34.990 --> 00:43:40.120 align:middle line:84%
So the interest on the federal
debt is going to the people.

00:43:40.120 --> 00:43:43.410 align:middle line:90%
It is their pension basically.

00:43:43.410 --> 00:43:51.500 align:middle line:84%
It's sort of like a dividend for
saving and for being Japanese.

00:43:51.500 --> 00:43:53.640 align:middle line:84%
So all the money is
staying in Japan.

00:43:53.640 --> 00:43:56.510 align:middle line:84%
They don't owe it to
foreign creditors.

00:43:56.510 --> 00:44:01.260 align:middle line:84%
And meanwhile,
they have-- they're

00:44:01.260 --> 00:44:04.150 align:middle line:84%
at the top of the market
for all these electronics.

00:44:04.150 --> 00:44:06.770 align:middle line:84%
And I mean their export
business is huge.

00:44:06.770 --> 00:44:09.030 align:middle line:90%
They're doing very, very well.

00:44:09.030 --> 00:44:12.720 align:middle line:84%
But they've sort of
hidden behind this debt

00:44:12.720 --> 00:44:13.512 align:middle line:90%
to GDP ratio thing.

00:44:13.512 --> 00:44:14.886 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Because
they don't want

00:44:14.886 --> 00:44:16.760 align:middle line:84%
the rest of the world
to know exactly?

00:44:16.760 --> 00:44:20.410 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Well, there's a lot
of written out there about how

00:44:20.410 --> 00:44:23.230 align:middle line:84%
World War II was actually--
I mean if you want to get

00:44:23.230 --> 00:44:24.500 align:middle line:90%
into conspiracy theories--

00:44:24.500 --> 00:44:25.790 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Just a little bit.

00:44:25.790 --> 00:44:30.540 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: --that both Germany
and Japan were doing great

00:44:30.540 --> 00:44:32.160 align:middle line:84%
during the '30s
because they were just

00:44:32.160 --> 00:44:33.510 align:middle line:90%
printing their own money.

00:44:33.510 --> 00:44:40.160 align:middle line:84%
And so it was to bring them
down that-- World War II,

00:44:40.160 --> 00:44:43.150 align:middle line:84%
whether it was designed that way
or not, it did bring them down.

00:44:43.150 --> 00:44:46.190 align:middle line:84%
And so the Japanese could
see that if they wanted

00:44:46.190 --> 00:44:47.960 align:middle line:84%
to survive in this
system, they had

00:44:47.960 --> 00:44:49.410 align:middle line:90%
to be a little more discreet.

00:44:49.410 --> 00:44:50.980 align:middle line:90%
They couldn't just print.

00:44:50.980 --> 00:44:52.850 align:middle line:84%
So they borrowed
from their own bank

00:44:52.850 --> 00:44:54.900 align:middle line:84%
so it looked like
they were in debt.

00:44:54.900 --> 00:44:56.776 align:middle line:84%
But in fact, they were
in debt to themselves.

00:44:56.776 --> 00:44:58.066 align:middle line:90%
So they're still just printing.

00:44:58.066 --> 00:44:59.190 align:middle line:90%
But they're printing debt.

00:44:59.190 --> 00:45:00.940 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But what
they're doing is smart.

00:45:00.940 --> 00:45:02.149 align:middle line:90%
And we should be taking note.

00:45:02.149 --> 00:45:04.189 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about other
countries who have already

00:45:04.189 --> 00:45:06.260 align:middle line:84%
implemented the same kind
of banking in the past.

00:45:06.260 --> 00:45:08.140 align:middle line:84%
And there is-- and
I would like to get

00:45:08.140 --> 00:45:11.860 align:middle line:84%
to it if we have a chance--
there are some articles that

00:45:11.860 --> 00:45:15.130 align:middle line:84%
are starting to pop up about
a new kind of bank that

00:45:15.130 --> 00:45:17.390 align:middle line:84%
is specifically
investment oriented

00:45:17.390 --> 00:45:20.090 align:middle line:84%
banks for small and
medium sized businesses,

00:45:20.090 --> 00:45:21.920 align:middle line:90%
how we have a need for this now.

00:45:21.920 --> 00:45:23.850 align:middle line:84%
But let's talk about
Germany, for example,

00:45:23.850 --> 00:45:25.590 align:middle line:84%
and anywhere else
that has already

00:45:25.590 --> 00:45:28.190 align:middle line:84%
implemented this
kind of banking.

00:45:28.190 --> 00:45:30.240 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: In Germany
and Japan, they

00:45:30.240 --> 00:45:34.910 align:middle line:84%
have systems that are--
it's alternative banking

00:45:34.910 --> 00:45:40.400 align:middle line:84%
or public banking where they're
designed to serve the economy

00:45:40.400 --> 00:45:44.140 align:middle line:84%
and to serve the businesses,
rather than our type of banking

00:45:44.140 --> 00:45:46.750 align:middle line:90%
is designed to extract interest.

00:45:46.750 --> 00:45:49.430 align:middle line:84%
And so it's all
based on collateral,

00:45:49.430 --> 00:45:51.756 align:middle line:84%
which means only the
rich can get loans.

00:45:51.756 --> 00:45:53.130 align:middle line:84%
If you don't have
the collateral,

00:45:53.130 --> 00:45:54.470 align:middle line:90%
you can't get thee loan.

00:45:54.470 --> 00:45:57.400 align:middle line:84%
If you just have a good business
idea, you can't get a loan,

00:45:57.400 --> 00:46:00.090 align:middle line:90%
but in Germany and Japan--

00:46:00.090 --> 00:46:03.190 align:middle line:84%
Well, Japan's model is--
they're called keiretsu, where

00:46:03.190 --> 00:46:06.940 align:middle line:84%
you have a group of corporations
that own their own bank.

00:46:06.940 --> 00:46:09.950 align:middle line:84%
And so the bank funds
the corporations,

00:46:09.950 --> 00:46:12.227 align:middle line:84%
advances credit to
the corporations.

00:46:12.227 --> 00:46:14.060 align:middle line:84%
And they all put their
deposits in the bank.

00:46:14.060 --> 00:46:16.412 align:middle line:84%
And so they're really
borrowing from themselves.

00:46:16.412 --> 00:46:17.870 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It's a
closed loop again.

00:46:17.870 --> 00:46:18.110 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Mhm.

00:46:18.110 --> 00:46:18.730 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:46:18.730 --> 00:46:20.600 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: And in Germany,
it's the same deal,

00:46:20.600 --> 00:46:24.340 align:middle line:84%
where the public
banks are designed

00:46:24.340 --> 00:46:25.530 align:middle line:90%
to serve the businesses.

00:46:25.530 --> 00:46:27.610 align:middle line:90%
They take the long view.

00:46:27.610 --> 00:46:30.444 align:middle line:90%


00:46:30.444 --> 00:46:31.110 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:46:31.110 --> 00:46:31.390 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:31.390 --> 00:46:32.180 align:middle line:90%
So we have that.

00:46:32.180 --> 00:46:36.640 align:middle line:84%
And then we have the reflections
on the Bank of North Dakota.

00:46:36.640 --> 00:46:40.610 align:middle line:84%
And yet we can't seem
to find our way out

00:46:40.610 --> 00:46:43.024 align:middle line:84%
of this, because there seems
to be some resistance, which

00:46:43.024 --> 00:46:44.690 align:middle line:84%
could have something
to do with the fact

00:46:44.690 --> 00:46:48.350 align:middle line:84%
that the largest lobbying
group on Capitol Hill

00:46:48.350 --> 00:46:49.980 align:middle line:84%
happens to be the
banking industry.

00:46:49.980 --> 00:46:51.605 align:middle line:84%
Could that have
anything to do with why

00:46:51.605 --> 00:46:53.120 align:middle line:90%
we're not seeing these changes?

00:46:53.120 --> 00:46:53.370 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Right.

00:46:53.370 --> 00:46:53.530 align:middle line:90%
Completely.

00:46:53.530 --> 00:46:55.696 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You've been
speaking about this for years.

00:46:55.696 --> 00:46:57.515 align:middle line:84%
And others are on
board with you on this.

00:46:57.515 --> 00:46:59.640 align:middle line:84%
And we can, I think just
from the little bit you've

00:46:59.640 --> 00:47:02.460 align:middle line:84%
explained, we can
see the logic in it.

00:47:02.460 --> 00:47:03.520 align:middle line:90%
But it's not happening.

00:47:03.520 --> 00:47:08.260 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Well, the federal
level is locked up.

00:47:08.260 --> 00:47:09.830 align:middle line:90%
The banks own Congress.

00:47:09.830 --> 00:47:12.340 align:middle line:84%
That's been said and
that seems to be true.

00:47:12.340 --> 00:47:15.730 align:middle line:84%
But on this local level, there
are still things you could do.

00:47:15.730 --> 00:47:17.970 align:middle line:10%
The cities and the
counties are run

00:47:17.970 --> 00:47:20.880 align:middle line:10%
by a handful of
commissioners or councilmen.

00:47:20.880 --> 00:47:22.235 align:middle line:10%
And they're approachable.

00:47:22.235 --> 00:47:23.360 align:middle line:10%
And you could talk to them.

00:47:23.360 --> 00:47:25.630 align:middle line:10%
And so they could
very quietly-- this

00:47:25.630 --> 00:47:28.440 align:middle line:10%
is what I envision happening--
is this very quiet sort

00:47:28.440 --> 00:47:32.690 align:middle line:10%
of grassroots movement
where they just set up--

00:47:32.690 --> 00:47:34.140 align:middle line:10%
you could call it
something else,

00:47:34.140 --> 00:47:39.500 align:middle line:10%
like Washington state is
calling it an investment trust.

00:47:39.500 --> 00:47:42.600 align:middle line:84%
If you call it a public bank
you might be bringing down

00:47:42.600 --> 00:47:44.580 align:middle line:90%
the ire of the bankers.

00:47:44.580 --> 00:47:49.840 align:middle line:84%
But what you need is
a financial system

00:47:49.840 --> 00:47:53.250 align:middle line:84%
that serves the people,
where the profits go back

00:47:53.250 --> 00:47:54.050 align:middle line:90%
to the people.

00:47:54.050 --> 00:47:56.320 align:middle line:84%
And that is a
sustainable system.

00:47:56.320 --> 00:47:59.880 align:middle line:84%
And the model's been proven
globally and historically.

00:47:59.880 --> 00:48:02.380 align:middle line:84%
It's just that it's
always defeated

00:48:02.380 --> 00:48:11.470 align:middle line:84%
by the big international cartel
that is more powerful and more

00:48:11.470 --> 00:48:14.919 align:middle line:84%
based on this extractive
model of extracting interest.

00:48:14.919 --> 00:48:16.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And so
some of the articles

00:48:16.460 --> 00:48:18.334 align:middle line:84%
I've read recently--
there are only a couple.

00:48:18.334 --> 00:48:21.760 align:middle line:84%
They're just starting to surface
about some nebulous new banking

00:48:21.760 --> 00:48:23.480 align:middle line:90%
system coming up.

00:48:23.480 --> 00:48:25.780 align:middle line:84%
Francois Holland, the
new president in France,

00:48:25.780 --> 00:48:27.280 align:middle line:84%
is calling for it
and saying they're

00:48:27.280 --> 00:48:30.290 align:middle line:84%
going to roll their
public bank, which

00:48:30.290 --> 00:48:33.600 align:middle line:84%
is going to be for the
purpose of investing

00:48:33.600 --> 00:48:35.125 align:middle line:90%
in small to mid-size businesses.

00:48:35.125 --> 00:48:37.560 align:middle line:84%
They're going to be
rolling this model out

00:48:37.560 --> 00:48:40.370 align:middle line:84%
to help get the people back on
their feet again and to work.

00:48:40.370 --> 00:48:43.910 align:middle line:84%
But what I'm reading
is that, as you say,

00:48:43.910 --> 00:48:47.980 align:middle line:84%
this is not collateral-
or asset-backed lending.

00:48:47.980 --> 00:48:51.740 align:middle line:84%
The lending would be based
on cash flows of a company.

00:48:51.740 --> 00:48:53.570 align:middle line:84%
And there's a big
distinction here.

00:48:53.570 --> 00:48:55.130 align:middle line:90%
OK, so let's use an example.

00:48:55.130 --> 00:48:59.720 align:middle line:84%
Let's say your town does not
have a dog grooming parlor.

00:48:59.720 --> 00:49:00.507 align:middle line:90%
And you love dogs.

00:49:00.507 --> 00:49:02.090 align:middle line:84%
You know how to do
this thing, and you

00:49:02.090 --> 00:49:04.390 align:middle line:84%
want to set up a dog
grooming business.

00:49:04.390 --> 00:49:06.700 align:middle line:84%
And you're going to
the bank to say, hey,

00:49:06.700 --> 00:49:09.220 align:middle line:84%
I want to do my dog
grooming business.

00:49:09.220 --> 00:49:12.010 align:middle line:84%
What's the bank going to look
at under the current model,

00:49:12.010 --> 00:49:15.746 align:middle line:84%
the restrictive model,
versus that other new model?

00:49:15.746 --> 00:49:17.620 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Well, they'll
look at your buildings

00:49:17.620 --> 00:49:20.150 align:middle line:84%
and your physical
assets that they

00:49:20.150 --> 00:49:22.930 align:middle line:90%
can attach when you default.

00:49:22.930 --> 00:49:25.420 align:middle line:84%
And they're probably
expecting you to default.

00:49:25.420 --> 00:49:26.355 align:middle line:90%
I mean, that's--

00:49:26.355 --> 00:49:27.980 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So the
whole system's banking

00:49:27.980 --> 00:49:29.760 align:middle line:84%
on your failure,
no pun intended.

00:49:29.760 --> 00:49:30.450 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:49:30.450 --> 00:49:32.200 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They're
banking on your failure.

00:49:32.200 --> 00:49:35.210 align:middle line:84%
And then they're going to take
your stuff back and resell it?

00:49:35.210 --> 00:49:36.450 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Mhm.

00:49:36.450 --> 00:49:39.340 align:middle line:84%
But the other
model has been done

00:49:39.340 --> 00:49:42.840 align:middle line:84%
globally and
historically very well.

00:49:42.840 --> 00:49:47.320 align:middle line:84%
The Chinese, the Koreans,
the whole Asian model

00:49:47.320 --> 00:49:50.024 align:middle line:84%
is where you extend
credit to your businesses

00:49:50.024 --> 00:49:51.190 align:middle line:90%
and support your businesses.

00:49:51.190 --> 00:49:55.350 align:middle line:84%
In fact, we call that a
violation of the World Trade

00:49:55.350 --> 00:49:56.470 align:middle line:90%
Organization rules.

00:49:56.470 --> 00:49:57.740 align:middle line:90%
And we say, they're cheating.

00:49:57.740 --> 00:50:00.360 align:middle line:84%
They're supporting
their businesses

00:50:00.360 --> 00:50:05.160 align:middle line:84%
by letting them-- well, they're
called nonperforming loans.

00:50:05.160 --> 00:50:09.670 align:middle line:84%
But the way the Chinese did it,
they had no intention of-- they

00:50:09.670 --> 00:50:11.490 align:middle line:84%
don't call it-- these
are grants basically.

00:50:11.490 --> 00:50:13.406 align:middle line:84%
They're just supporting
their export business.

00:50:13.406 --> 00:50:15.720 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But isn't it more
of a genuine partnership

00:50:15.720 --> 00:50:19.250 align:middle line:84%
where the lender is looking
to help sustain the health

00:50:19.250 --> 00:50:21.500 align:middle line:90%
and longevity of a business?

00:50:21.500 --> 00:50:24.440 align:middle line:84%
And that is not what we've been
doing, certainly in the United

00:50:24.440 --> 00:50:25.830 align:middle line:90%
States, for quite a long time.

00:50:25.830 --> 00:50:27.345 align:middle line:84%
The industry hasn't
been doing it.

00:50:27.345 --> 00:50:27.970 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Right.

00:50:27.970 --> 00:50:30.290 align:middle line:84%
That's the German model,
the Japanese model.

00:50:30.290 --> 00:50:34.500 align:middle line:84%
It's the Islamic
model, usary-free--

00:50:34.500 --> 00:50:36.940 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Let's talk
about Islamic banking.

00:50:36.940 --> 00:50:40.550 align:middle line:84%
There you're talking about
essentially a lack of interest,

00:50:40.550 --> 00:50:41.680 align:middle line:90%
no pun intended.

00:50:41.680 --> 00:50:42.670 align:middle line:90%
There is no interest.

00:50:42.670 --> 00:50:43.380 align:middle line:90%
[BOTH LAUGH]

00:50:43.380 --> 00:50:44.790 align:middle line:90%
There's no interest.

00:50:44.790 --> 00:50:45.760 align:middle line:90%
But there is a fee.

00:50:45.760 --> 00:50:47.890 align:middle line:84%
Can you explain how
Islamic banking works?

00:50:47.890 --> 00:50:50.010 align:middle line:84%
Some people have heard
about this already.

00:50:50.010 --> 00:50:51.610 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Well, from
what I've read,

00:50:51.610 --> 00:50:54.940 align:middle line:90%
they're still experimenting.

00:50:54.940 --> 00:50:58.620 align:middle line:84%
It was in the Koran that
interest is forbidden.

00:50:58.620 --> 00:51:03.900 align:middle line:84%
But it wasn't really
tried on a national level

00:51:03.900 --> 00:51:08.670 align:middle line:84%
until Iran became a
religious state in the 1970s.

00:51:08.670 --> 00:51:13.880 align:middle line:84%
And that's where most of the
big Islamic banks are right now.

00:51:13.880 --> 00:51:19.370 align:middle line:84%
But some critics, like
some Islamic clerics,

00:51:19.370 --> 00:51:22.960 align:middle line:84%
say that they're cheating
and that they're really

00:51:22.960 --> 00:51:24.440 align:middle line:90%
getting interest by other means.

00:51:24.440 --> 00:51:28.350 align:middle line:84%
Because what they do is,
say if they make a loan,

00:51:28.350 --> 00:51:30.080 align:middle line:84%
they double the
price of the house.

00:51:30.080 --> 00:51:32.542 align:middle line:84%
So you pay twice as much
over the time of the loan.

00:51:32.542 --> 00:51:33.500 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Is that true?

00:51:33.500 --> 00:51:35.291 align:middle line:84%
I mean, from what you've
been able to tell?

00:51:35.291 --> 00:51:36.780 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Some.

00:51:36.780 --> 00:51:39.260 align:middle line:84%
I haven't heard of a
really good, effective,

00:51:39.260 --> 00:51:41.540 align:middle line:90%
interest-free model yet.

00:51:41.540 --> 00:51:43.790 align:middle line:84%
So that's why I like
the public banking model

00:51:43.790 --> 00:51:45.610 align:middle line:84%
where you charge
interest, which is

00:51:45.610 --> 00:51:48.970 align:middle line:84%
a way of-- If you have
a 4% default rate,

00:51:48.970 --> 00:51:51.160 align:middle line:84%
you're going to have to
charge 4% interest just

00:51:51.160 --> 00:51:53.840 align:middle line:84%
to make up for the defaults or
you're going to go bankrupt.

00:51:53.840 --> 00:51:56.740 align:middle line:84%
So I like the model of
the interest going back

00:51:56.740 --> 00:52:00.390 align:middle line:84%
to the people, either
as a cooperative model

00:52:00.390 --> 00:52:03.600 align:middle line:84%
or as a public model,
which seems to me

00:52:03.600 --> 00:52:07.420 align:middle line:84%
overcomes any ethical
objections but still

00:52:07.420 --> 00:52:09.830 align:middle line:90%
is a sustainable system.

00:52:09.830 --> 00:52:13.690 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So going back for just
a moment to the person who--

00:52:13.690 --> 00:52:15.690 align:middle line:84%
so let's say this person
applying for their loan

00:52:15.690 --> 00:52:17.189 align:middle line:84%
to start their dog
grooming business

00:52:17.189 --> 00:52:18.650 align:middle line:90%
doesn't have a building.

00:52:18.650 --> 00:52:20.190 align:middle line:84%
Now under this
other model you're

00:52:20.190 --> 00:52:22.550 align:middle line:84%
talking about, say if
it's a state-owned bank,

00:52:22.550 --> 00:52:25.260 align:middle line:84%
and if we're looking at
not lending money based

00:52:25.260 --> 00:52:28.670 align:middle line:84%
on assets but on cash flow,
how would a little business

00:52:28.670 --> 00:52:30.360 align:middle line:84%
like that work within
this closed loop

00:52:30.360 --> 00:52:32.645 align:middle line:84%
model you're talking
about, a locally owned

00:52:32.645 --> 00:52:36.350 align:middle line:90%
or state owned banks?

00:52:36.350 --> 00:52:38.590 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: You would still
need some sort of record

00:52:38.590 --> 00:52:41.975 align:middle line:84%
to show that you had
a cash flow, that you

00:52:41.975 --> 00:52:43.640 align:middle line:90%
were going to produce something.

00:52:43.640 --> 00:52:48.240 align:middle line:84%
Even in North Dakota, we have
a retired Bank of North Dakota

00:52:48.240 --> 00:52:50.630 align:middle line:84%
man on our advisory
board, and he

00:52:50.630 --> 00:52:53.670 align:middle line:84%
says we are not
development people.

00:52:53.670 --> 00:52:58.030 align:middle line:84%
We do not fund businesses
that are going to go bankrupt.

00:52:58.030 --> 00:53:01.880 align:middle line:84%
We're bankers, and we look at
the viability of the business

00:53:01.880 --> 00:53:03.650 align:middle line:90%
as anyone else would.

00:53:03.650 --> 00:53:08.110 align:middle line:84%
In fact, more so than
banks in other states,

00:53:08.110 --> 00:53:10.790 align:middle line:84%
which were selling their
loans off to investors

00:53:10.790 --> 00:53:12.349 align:middle line:90%
so they don't care whether the--

00:53:12.349 --> 00:53:13.390 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Business fails.

00:53:13.390 --> 00:53:14.115 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Right.

00:53:14.115 --> 00:53:15.240 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That makes sense.

00:53:15.240 --> 00:53:16.870 align:middle line:84%
So you're entering
into a partnership.

00:53:16.870 --> 00:53:18.720 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: It is a partnership.

00:53:18.720 --> 00:53:21.840 align:middle line:84%
They want the business to
succeed because they're

00:53:21.840 --> 00:53:23.620 align:middle line:84%
going to keep that
loan on their books.

00:53:23.620 --> 00:53:25.370 align:middle line:84%
And they don't want
it going into default.

00:53:25.370 --> 00:53:28.290 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well let's go
into more personal levels.

00:53:28.290 --> 00:53:30.890 align:middle line:84%
People watching this have
feelings about all of this.

00:53:30.890 --> 00:53:36.460 align:middle line:84%
And one segment, a big
segment now, feels,

00:53:36.460 --> 00:53:37.880 align:middle line:90%
let them crash and burn.

00:53:37.880 --> 00:53:40.550 align:middle line:90%
These are horrible practices.

00:53:40.550 --> 00:53:44.210 align:middle line:84%
We've been enslaved to
our monetary systems.

00:53:44.210 --> 00:53:46.660 align:middle line:84%
Our government's enslaved,
our politicians are enslaved.

00:53:46.660 --> 00:53:49.140 align:middle line:90%
So let them crash and burn.

00:53:49.140 --> 00:53:51.610 align:middle line:84%
What's the reality
of the banking system

00:53:51.610 --> 00:53:54.210 align:middle line:84%
crashing and burning from
a pragmatic point of view?

00:53:54.210 --> 00:53:56.080 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Well, the
too big to fail

00:53:56.080 --> 00:54:00.310 align:middle line:84%
banks really are too
big to just let them go.

00:54:00.310 --> 00:54:03.270 align:middle line:84%
Instead of-- I mean, they've
got their little tentacles

00:54:03.270 --> 00:54:05.180 align:middle line:90%
in everything globally.

00:54:05.180 --> 00:54:07.040 align:middle line:90%
I would feel quite nervous .

00:54:07.040 --> 00:54:08.970 align:middle line:90%
You couldn't travel anymore.

00:54:08.970 --> 00:54:11.970 align:middle line:84%
What are you going to
use for your Visa card?

00:54:11.970 --> 00:54:14.834 align:middle line:84%
But they are not too
big to nationalize.

00:54:14.834 --> 00:54:16.250 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that would
be the solution

00:54:16.250 --> 00:54:18.740 align:middle line:84%
it seems to me is we the
people should take them over.

00:54:18.740 --> 00:54:19.840 align:middle line:90%
Keep the bank.

00:54:19.840 --> 00:54:20.820 align:middle line:90%
Change the name.

00:54:20.820 --> 00:54:23.540 align:middle line:90%
And make it ours.

00:54:23.540 --> 00:54:26.922 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: What do we, if we're
part of the 80% on the bottom,

00:54:26.922 --> 00:54:28.630 align:middle line:84%
most of us, and almost
everybody watching

00:54:28.630 --> 00:54:31.380 align:middle line:84%
is probably part of
the 80% on the bottom.

00:54:31.380 --> 00:54:33.212 align:middle line:90%
What do we do now?

00:54:33.212 --> 00:54:34.920 align:middle line:84%
I mean, what do we do
with whatever money

00:54:34.920 --> 00:54:36.520 align:middle line:90%
we may still have?

00:54:36.520 --> 00:54:37.270 align:middle line:90%
Are their choices?

00:54:37.270 --> 00:54:40.770 align:middle line:84%
Do you stay with the big
privately owned banks?

00:54:40.770 --> 00:54:44.380 align:middle line:84%
Do you find other little
local credit unions?

00:54:44.380 --> 00:54:48.320 align:middle line:90%
What do we do with our money?

00:54:48.320 --> 00:54:50.030 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: That is difficult.

00:54:50.030 --> 00:54:53.190 align:middle line:90%
It depends on who you are.

00:54:53.190 --> 00:54:55.360 align:middle line:84%
Credit unions are a
great idea, of course.

00:54:55.360 --> 00:54:57.090 align:middle line:90%
And that is a cooperative model.

00:54:57.090 --> 00:55:00.560 align:middle line:84%
But there are limitations
to a credit union.

00:55:00.560 --> 00:55:04.400 align:middle line:84%
And if you have your own small
business, you may find, I mean,

00:55:04.400 --> 00:55:07.830 align:middle line:84%
I've heard people say that
they just can't work well.

00:55:07.830 --> 00:55:11.110 align:middle line:84%
In fact, I know-- there are
several cities in California

00:55:11.110 --> 00:55:13.860 align:middle line:84%
that were talking about
moving their money out

00:55:13.860 --> 00:55:16.300 align:middle line:90%
of Wall Street into local banks.

00:55:16.300 --> 00:55:19.540 align:middle line:84%
And the credit unions are
not big enough for that.

00:55:19.540 --> 00:55:23.290 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So can we use
established local banks?

00:55:23.290 --> 00:55:24.410 align:middle line:90%
Can they come on board?

00:55:24.410 --> 00:55:27.630 align:middle line:84%
Are they allowed to come on
board with a, say a mandate

00:55:27.630 --> 00:55:29.460 align:middle line:84%
or request on
behalf of the people

00:55:29.460 --> 00:55:32.290 align:middle line:84%
to start serving in
this public capacity?

00:55:32.290 --> 00:55:34.170 align:middle line:84%
Do they have the
right to do that?

00:55:34.170 --> 00:55:35.670 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: I guess I
don't understand.

00:55:35.670 --> 00:55:38.180 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: If you have
a local bank, OK?

00:55:38.180 --> 00:55:40.960 align:middle line:84%
Not a B of A or something, but
a local bank that's established,

00:55:40.960 --> 00:55:43.280 align:middle line:84%
can they go into partnership
with that community

00:55:43.280 --> 00:55:46.240 align:middle line:84%
to become more of the
model you're talking about?

00:55:46.240 --> 00:55:48.910 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: Well, in
North Dakota, it's

00:55:48.910 --> 00:55:50.760 align:middle line:84%
the bank of North
Dakota that allows

00:55:50.760 --> 00:55:57.542 align:middle line:84%
these small banks to expand and
take on a lot more deposits.

00:55:57.542 --> 00:55:59.250 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So we have
to lobby on a larger

00:55:59.250 --> 00:56:00.450 align:middle line:90%
level it's sounding like.

00:56:00.450 --> 00:56:01.180 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Yeah.

00:56:01.180 --> 00:56:01.510 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: We do.

00:56:01.510 --> 00:56:02.240 align:middle line:90%
>>BROWN: Well, yeah.

00:56:02.240 --> 00:56:04.656 align:middle line:84%
The first thing-- you either
have to go to your-- approach

00:56:04.656 --> 00:56:07.210 align:middle line:90%
your legislator-- but local.

00:56:07.210 --> 00:56:09.140 align:middle line:90%
Go local.

00:56:09.140 --> 00:56:10.810 align:middle line:84%
We don't have time
to go into the county

00:56:10.810 --> 00:56:12.070 align:middle line:84%
bank possibilities
I don't think.

00:56:12.070 --> 00:56:13.028 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No, we don't.

00:56:13.028 --> 00:56:14.862 align:middle line:84%
>>BROWN: But you could
fix the real estate--

